{[%csl Gb6,Gd5][%cal Ye4d5] This structure arises in the variation 6.a4 g6!?
as White usually plays a4-a5 at some point, cramping Black's queenside. Since
White enjoys a small space advantage, Black needs to exchange some pieces in
order to free his position. One common idea for White is to play Nd5. In this
case, after Bxd5 exd5, he can put pressure along the e-file. Black should keep
the knights on the board, as the squares c5 and e5 are very stable posts. In
order to drive the knights back from these squares, White should go for some
concessions. The best scenario for Black is leaving White with the
light-squared bishop, as this bishop is his worse minor piece.}  *

