1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 g6 $5 {The practical
advantage of this version of Dragon is that White is deprived of the
aggressive lines with 0-0-0.} 7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Qd2 Nxd4 (
10... Bd7 11. f3 Rc8 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. a5 $1 {Pichot, A (2556)-Asis Gargatagli,
H (2526) Barcelona Rapid CAT-ARG 2018 (1.3) 1-0}) 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. a5 $1 {
[%csl Gb6] The inclusion of a4/a6 gives White the opportunity of seizing space
on the queenside.} Rc8 13. Rfd1 (13. Bb6 {doesn't really disturb Black.} Qe8 $1
{[%cal Yf6d7]} 14. Rfd1 Nd7 15. Bd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Qd8 $11 {[%cal Yd8c7,Yc7b8,
Yc7c4]}) 13... Qc7 14. Qe3 {This kind of position is often chosen by technical
players who like to keep a small edge in a risk-free position. He can keep
improving his pieces step by step, waiting for his opponent to make a mistake.}
({Another game went} 14. h3 {but Black followed with a plan which is similar
to the text.} Rfe8 15. Ra3 Nd7 $1 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Kg8 18. Rd2 {[%cal
Yc3d5]} Qc5 $1 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 $11 {Adams,M (2715)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2729) 9th
London Classic 2017 (6.4) 0-1}) 14... Nd7 $1 {Exchanges are welcome for Black
as he has some lack of space. In such kind of positions, even the exchange of
the dark-squared bishops is okay for Black.} 15. Rd2 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Bxd4 16.
Qxd4 Qc5 $1 17. Qxc5 Rxc5 18. Nd5 Bxd5 $1 {The las important exchange. The
endgame is equal.} 19. exd5 Ne5 20. b3 $6 {This move is unnecessary and
positionally bad. There's absolutely no reason for White to place his pawns on
the same square as his bishop, leaving a lot of weak dark-squares on the
queenside. This is the beginning of the problems.} (20. c3 {was the right move}
Nc4 21. Bxc4 Rxc4 22. Re2 Re8 23. Re3 Rc5 24. Rd3 Rec8 25. Kf1 $11) 20... Rc3
$1 {[%cal Yf8c8] Blocking the queenside.} ({White was probably hoping for} 
20... Rfc8 21. f4 Nd7 22. c4 {[%cal Yb3b4] with nice prospects on the
queenside.}) 21. f4 Nd7 22. Re1 (22. Bc4 {"traps" the rook, but White is not
able to take advantage of it} Rc8 23. Re1 Kf8 24. Kf2 Rc5 25. Ra1 b5 $1 26.
axb6 Nxb6 $17) 22... Rc5 23. Ra1 Rc3 24. Re1 Re8 $1 25. Bc4 Kf8 $1 {After
defending e7, Black is ready to make progress in queenside.} 26. Kf2 (26. Rde2
b5 $1 27. axb6 Nxb6 28. Bxa6 Nxd5 29. g3 Nb4 $17 {[%csl Ya6,Yc2]}) 26... Rc8
27. Re3 ({The move} 27. Rde2 {doesn't work due to} b5 $1 28. axb6 Nxb6 29. Bxa6
(29. Rxe7 Nxc4 30. bxc4 R8xc4 $17 {[%csl Rc2,Rf4]}) 29... R8c7 $15 {[%csl Yc2,
Yd5] and Black regains the pawn keeping an annoying pressure on the queenside.}
) 27... Rxe3 28. Kxe3 Rc5 {[%csl Ga5] The pawn that once was the cause of
White's easier play is lost.} 29. Rd1 Rxa5 $17 {Sjugirov converts his
advantage with an excellent play.} 30. Kd4 b5 31. Be2 b4 $1 32. Kc4 (32. Bc4
Nb6 33. g3 Rc5 {[%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4]}) 32... Rc5+ $1 33. Kxb4 a5+ 34. Ka4 (34.
Ka3 Rxc2 35. Bf3 Nc5 $19) 34... Nb6+ 35. Ka3 Nxd5 $19 36. g3 Ne3 37. Rc1 g5 $5
{Black creates a passed pawn in the centre.} (37... Rxc2 38. Rxc2 Nxc2+ 39. Ka4
Nd4 40. Bc4 e6 $19 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 38. fxg5 Rxg5 39. c3 Rc5 40. Bf3 Ke8 41. Ka4
Kd8 42. Rb1 $2 Rxc3 43. Kxa5 d5 44. Kb5 d4 45. b4 Nc4 0-1

