{It seems that White has good prospects advancing the passed pawn. How should
Black play?} 33... Nc7 $1 34. b5 (34. Rc8 Rb7 35. Kf2 Kf6 36. Ke3 e5 {[%cal
Yc7e6] seems holdable for Black}) 34... Ra8 $1 35. Rb7 (35. Rxa8 Nxa8 {[%cal
Ya8b6] and the knight blocks both pawns} 36. c4 dxc4 37. Bxc4 Kf6 38. Kf2 Nb6
39. Bb3 Ke7 40. Ke3 Kd6 41. Kd4 f6 $11) 35... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ye8d6] Black
manages to nicely coordinate his pieces in this endgame.} 36. c4 $2 (36. b6 {
was better} Ra1+ 37. Kf2 Rb1 38. Ke3 (38. Rb8 Nf6 {[%cal Yf6d7]}) 38... Rb3 39.
Kd4 Nd6 40. Rb8 Nf5+ 41. Kc5 Rxc3+ 42. Kb4 Rc2 $13 {although things are very
unclear now}) 36... Nd6 $1 37. Rc7 dxc4 38. Bxc4 Ra1+ 39. Kf2 Rc1 {[%csl Yc4]
and the only way to avoid big material losses for White is giving up the passed
pawn:} 40. b6 Nxc4 41. b7 Rb1 42. Rxc4 Rxb7 $17 {Adams,M (2715)-Nepomniachtchi,
I (2729) 9th London Classic 2017 (6.4) 0-1 Black managed to win the rook
endgame -} *

