1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nb3 (7. Nde2 {
and}) (7. Nf3 $5 {are other options}) 7... Be7 8. Bg2 (8. a4 {prevents b7-b5
but gives Black another nice option of development} Nc6 $1 9. Bg2 Nb4 $1 {
[%csl Gb4][%cal Yb8c6,Yc6b4] This is a very important idea to remember. If
White plays a2-a4 with the knight still on b8, Black can go for Nc6-b4,
incresing the control over the d5-square.} 10. Bg5 Be6 $1 11. O-O Rc8 $1 {
[%csl Yc2,Yd5] ;Guo,A (2219)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2451) SPICE Cup Open 2017 (4.
18) 0-1 The quick development of Black's queenside gives him a nice position.
The d5-square is well protected and Black retains his queenside pressure.})
8... O-O 9. O-O b5 $5 (9... Be6 {is the most played}) 10. a4 $1 {This is a
typical way to exploit Black's overextended queenside. The advance a2-a4 works
very well when Black is underdeveloped.} b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Ra7 13. Be3
Be6 $1 (13... Rd7 $2 14. Na5 $1 $16 {[%csl Yb8,Yc8] leaves Black in an
unpleasant position}) 14. Qd3 (14. Qd2 {is not dangerous for Black} Rb7 15. f4
Nd7 $11) 14... Ra8 $5 {Maybe this is the simplest way to solve all the
problems.} (14... Rb7 {[%csl Yb8] seems slightly inferior as Black has some
problems to develop the b8-knight now.} 15. Rfc1 $1 Qc7 16. c3 $1 {a very
strong move} Bc4 (16... Bxb3 17. cxb4 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Yd3b3]}) 17. Qc2 Be6 18.
Qd1 Qd8 19. Bf1 $1 {[%csl Ga6]} bxc3 20. Rxc3 Bg5 $2 {This usually favorable
exchange does not work in the concrete position.} 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. Bc4 $1 Bxc4
23. Rxc4 Nd7 24. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Ga6,Gd6] ;Ponomariov,R (2734)-Safarli,E (2620)
Istanbul ol (Men) 40th 2012 (10.2) 1-0 White has a pleasant edge due to
Black's weaknesses.}) 15. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] The threat is f4-f5, disturbing the
well placed bishop on e6.} (15. a5 {seems natural and good, but since a6 is
defended now, Black simply continues with} Nd7 {[%cal Yd7c5]} 16. Nd2 $5 {
avoiding the forced exchanges after Nc5} Qc7 17. Rfc1 Rfc8 18. c3 Nc5 $1 19.
Qe2 Qb7 $11 {Atabayev,M (2493)-Kelires,A (2384) Budapest FS03 GM 2015 (3) 1-0})
15... Qc7 {[%csl Gc4]} 16. Nd2 (16. Rfc1 Rc8 $1 {prevents the idea c2-c3.})
16... a5 $1 {Now the queenside pawns are safe.} 17. Rf2 $5 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3]
White keeps some pressure along the f-file and vacates the f1-square to
execute the maneuver Nf1-e3.} (17. f5 Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 17... f6 {This is
the most solid way to keep the center intact.} (17... exf4 $5 {also gave Black
a nice position} 18. gxf4 Nd7 19. Bd4 (19. f5 $2 Ne5 $17) 19... Bh4 $1 20. Re2
Rac8 21. Nf3 Bf6 22. Rd2 Bc4 23. Qe3 Rfe8 $15 {Smirin,I (2637)-Belov,V (2561)
Biel MTO op 41st 2008 (8) 0-1}) 18. f5 $6 {I don't like this decision. Now,
Black enjoys a stability in the center. Later on, he can proceed with his
queenside play.} (18. Bh3 $5 {was an interesting idea} Bf7 (18... Bxh3 $2 19.
Qd5+ {[%csl Ra8]}) 19. Rd1 Na6 20. Nb3 {with chances for both sides. The
tension in the center makes difficult for Black to find a constructive plan})
18... Bf7 19. Rc1 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black has a nice position and starts
thinking about his own plans: Nc5 or a well prepared d6-d5 break.} 20. c4 bxc3
$5 {The most ambitious.} (20... Nc5 {is nice, but probably just equal}) 21.
Qxc3 Qb8 22. Rff1 $6 (22. Nc4 $142 Nb4 23. b3 Rd8 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 22... Nb4 $1
{Suddenly, Black has the threats of Na2 and d6-d5.} 23. Qc7 Qe8 $1 {Grischuk
keeps more pieces on the board in order to make White's decisions harder.} 24.
Qb7 (24. Nc4 $2 Rc8 {[%csl Gc4]}) 24... Rb8 25. Qa7 Ra8 26. Qb7 Rb8 27. Qa7 d5
$1 {Finally, Black opens the centre and takes the initiative.} 28. exd5 (28.
Qxa5 d4 29. Bf2 Nd3 30. Rc2 Bd8 $1 {[%csl Ra5] surprisingly, the queen has not
squares} 31. Qa6 Nb4 $19) 28... Nxd5 29. Bc5 $2 {Hou blunders in a position
that was already difficult.} (29. Bxd5 {was the best chance for White} Bxd5 30.
Qxa5 Ba8 $1 {[%csl Ya8] White will suffer trying to defend the light squares,
but he has chances}) 29... Ra8 30. Qb7 Rb8 31. Qa7 Ra8 32. Qb7 Bxc5+ $1 33.
Rxc5 Rb8 34. Qxf7+ {Desperate, but other options were not that impressive.} ({
For example} 34. Qa7 Ne3 $1 35. Rf2 Rxb2 {and Black is simply winning} 36. Qxa5
(36. Rxa5 Nd1 $1 37. Re2 Qd8 $19 {[%csl Rd2]}) 36... Nxg2 37. Kxg2 Ra2 {
[%csl Ga4]} 38. Rb5 Qc6+ 39. Kh3 e4 $19) 34... Rxf7 35. Bxd5 Kh8 36. Rfc1 (36.
Bxf7 Qxf7 37. Rxa5 Qc7 38. Rb5 Rxb5 39. axb5 Qc2 $19) 36... Rd7 37. Bc6 Qd8 38.
Bxd7 Qxd7 39.Ne4 h5 {An impressive win by Grischuk, showing that even in such
apparently closed positions Black is able to take the initiative if White is
not careful.} 0-1

