1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nde2 Be7 8. Bg2
b5 9. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye2c3] A very simple way to occupy the d5-square
and improve the e2-knight. This line promises a tiny advantage for White. As
Wojtaszek shows, however, Black has sufficient counterplay.} (9. a4 {is
harmless here because after} b4 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Ra7 12. Be3 Be6 $1 13.
Qd2 Rb7 {[%csl Ye2] White does not have a good way to improve his e2-knight.})
(9. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge2g3] used to be the main idea} Nbd7 $1 {Black has a good
reason to keep the c8-bishop on his initial square.} 10. g4 b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12.
exd5 (12. Qxd5 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6] and the rook is taboo}) 12... a5 {[%cal
Yc8a6] Now the bishop will occupy the diagonal a6-f1. After} 13. O-O h5 $1 {
Alekseev, E (2708)-Dominguez Perez, L (2708) Biel GM 41st 2008 (8) 0-1 is an
unexpected way to take the initiative for Black. I think this is a good reason
to prefer the text instead of the old-fashioned h3-g4 plan. Black won a nice
game in}) 9... Nbd7 $1 ({With a pawn on b5, the idea} 9... Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Ra7 {
does not work very well since after} 11. Be3 Rb7 12. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Ye2c3,Yc3d5]
White can improve the knight}) 10. Nec3 Nb6 $1 {Black is planning to exchange
all the knights, thus making it harder for White to occupy the d5-square.} (
10... Bb7 11. a4 $1 {gave White a pleasant edge in many games}) 11. Nxe7 (11.
Nxf6+ {was played by Giri} Bxf6 12. O-O O-O 13. b3 {Giri, A (2782)-Vachier
Lagrave,M (2789) GCT Blitz YourNextMove 2018 (2.5) 0-1} Qc7 14. Qd2 Be6 15. Ba3
Rfc8 $1 {with a nice counterplay for Black.}) 11... Qxe7 12. Bg5 O-O {Again,
the most precise move. Wojtaszek improves on his previous game against Giri.} (
12... h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. a4 $1 bxa4 (14... b4 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Ra7 17.
Qc6+ Bd7 18. Qb6 $16 {[%csl Ga7,Gb4]}) 15. Nxa4 Nxa4 16. Rxa4 {[%csl Ga6,Gd6] ;
Giri,A (2784)-Wojtaszek,R (2723) Qatar Masters op 2015 (3) 1-0 White's better
pawn structure provides a small but long-lasting advantage -}) 13. O-O (13. a4
{gives nothing for White now} b4 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Bg4 $1 {
and Black is fine}) (13. Qf3 Be6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 {was also harmless
} 16. O-O-O b4 $1 17. Nd5 $6 (17. Ne2 $142 Rfd8 18. b3 a5 19. Rd2 Kf8 $11 {
[%cal Yf8e7]}) 17... Nxd5 $1 18. exd5 Bf5 {[%csl Yc2] ;Karjakin,S (2781)
-Vachier Lagrave,M (2796) Norway Chess 5th 2017 (9) 1/2 and Black had even an
easier game due the pressure on c2 -}) 13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black has no
problems here, as his remaning minor pieces are ready to fight for the
d5-square.} 15. a4 {It is difficult to imagine how can White create some
unbalance without this move. Nevertheless, even this move does not give an
advantage.} (15. b3 Bb7 16. Qd2 Rac8 {seems totally fine for Black}) 15... b4
16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 {Black's idea now is very nice to remember:} Be6 $1 18.
Qxd6 a5 $1 $44 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Ya8c8,Yf8d8] I think that sacrificing the
d6-pawn is a very interesting idea from a practical point of view: Instead of
continuously caring about its defense, Black gives the pawn away in order to
obtain open files and some tempos to attack the misplaced white queen.} 19. Qb6
{Other options give Black good counterplay as well.} (19. Qd2 Rac8 20. Rac1
Rfd8 21. Qe3 Qe7 $1 22. f4 $5 (22. Qb6 Qc5 $1 23. Qxc5 Rxc5 {[%cal Yd8c8,Gd8d2]
regains the pawn at least}) 22... Bd7 $1 {[%csl Ya4]} 23. b3 Bg4 $1 {[%cal
Gc8c3] and White even has problems already} 24. c3 bxc3 25. Rxc3 Qb4 $1 26.
Rxc8 Rxc8 27. fxe5 Rc3 28. Qf4 Be6 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3]}) (19. c3 bxc3 20. bxc3
Rac8 21. Rfc1 Rfd8 22. Qb6 Rd2 $1 $132) 19... Rfc8 20. Rfc1 Qe7 $1 21. Qe3 (21.
h3 Qc5 $1 {and Black regains the pawn} 22. Qxc5 Rxc5 23. Bf1 Rac8 {[%csl Yc2]})
21... Rc5 {The pressure on c2 will prevent White from making any progress.} 22.
Bf1 Rac8 23. Ba6 (23. Bd3 Bc4 $1 24. Rd1 (24. Bxc4 Rxc4 25. c3 Qc7 {wins the
pawn back.}) 24... Bxd3 25. cxd3 Rc2 26. d4 $5 (26. Rab1 Qe6 {[%cal Ge6b3]}) (
26. Rac1 Qd7 27. Rxc2 Rxc2 28. b3 Qd4 $1 $15 {[%cal Yc2c3]}) 26... exd4 27.
Qxd4 R8c4 $1 28. Qd8+ Qxd8 29. Rxd8+ Kh7 {[%csl Gb2,Ge4]}) (23. c3 Qc7 24. Ba6
bxc3 $1 25. bxc3 (25. Bxc8 $2 cxb2 $19) 25... Ra8 26. Bb5 Rc8 27. Ra3 Bc4 $1
28. Bxc4 Rxc4 {[%csl Ga4,Gc3,Ge4][%cal Yc7c6] and Black has nice pressure.})
23... R8c6 $1 {The c7-square should be available for the queen. Navara didn't
find anything better than repeating the moves.} 24. Bb5 Rc8 25. Ba6 R8c6 26.
Bb5 Rc8 27. Ba6 1/2-1/2

