1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg5
{The main idea of this solid line consists of fighting for the d5-square.} Be6
9. Bxf6 $1 {White should play this before ...Nbd7, in order to make Black
waste some time to organize his pieces again.} Bxf6 10. Qd3 {[%cal Ge1c1]} (10.
Nd5 {This move removes the pressure from d6 and Black can continue with the
development.} Nd7 11. Qd3 Bg5 $1 {preventing 0-0-0} 12. Rd1 O-O 13. c3 Kh8 14.
O-O Rc8 15. Bf3 g6 {[%cal Yf7f5] ;Kotsur,P (2548)-Gelfand,B (2738) Wch Blitz
6th 2012 (24) 0-1 and Black had good prospects on the kingside -}) 10... Be7 $1
{[%cal Yb8d7]} 11. O-O-O Nd7 12. g3 {[%cal Yf2f4] By means of f2-f4-f5 White
wants to increase the control of d5. This idea is the main justification of
White's 0-0-0. Black should now organize counterplay on the queenside.} b5 $1
13. f4 (13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 {Taghizadeh,R (2259)-Liang,A (2383) North
American op 25th 2015 (9) 1/2} Ra7 $5 15. Kb1 O-O 16. f4 Qb6 {[%cal Yf8c8,
Ya7c7] and Black is fine}) 13... O-O ({Black could leave the king in the
center and continue to concentrate forces on the queenside:} 13... Rc8 $1 14.
f5 Bc4 15. Qf3 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 (16. Nxe2 b4 $1 {[%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4]}) {and here
the thematic} 16... Rxc3 $5 {offers a typical compensation for Black} 17. bxc3
Qc7 18. Rd3 Nb6 $44 {Black's play is very simple in such positions. He should
follow with simple moves such as ...0-0, ...Rc8, and ...Nc4 or ...Na4. There
are no open files for the white rooks while the c1-king will be vulnerable in
a long-term.}) 14. f5 Bc4 15. Qf3 Bxe2 (15... Nb6 {or}) (15... Rc8 {were more
natural}) 16. Qxe2 Nb6 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 {[%csl Yb3,Ge7] Strategically
speaking, White reached the ideal piece configuration - good knight versus bad
bishop. The only remaining task is maneuvering the knight from b3 to d5 after
which White would be able to claim a clear advantage. But in practice, things
are not so simple since the white king is vulnerable on the queenside. That is
why Black's counterplay is very dangerous.} Qc7 19. Kb1 (19. Nd2 Rfc8 20. Nf1
Bg5+ $1 21. Kb1 Qc4 $1 {is a nice example of White's practical difficulties})
19... Rfc8 20. h4 Rab8 (20... Qc4 $5 21. Qxc4 Rxc4 22. Re1 g6 $132) 21. Qd2 Qc4
(21... Qb6 $142 {[%cal Yc8c4]}) 22. Re1 Ra8 {Black has also some difficulties
to advance the pawns.} 23. Rd3 Qc7 24. Rc3 Qb6 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Nc1 {White
starts the knight's journey.} a5 $1 27. Nd3 {White clearly underestimated the
counterplay.} (27. a3 b4 28. axb4 axb4 29. Qd3 Ra8 30. Qb3 {[%cal Yc1d3,Yc1a2]}
Ra5 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 27... b4 $1 {While White wastes time maneuvering the
knight, Black should take active actions on the queenside.} 28. Nf2 (28. b3 $5
{was a nice try to stop Black's queenside play.} Rc3 29. Rd1 Qd4 30. Qg2 Qe3
$13) 28... a4 29. Ng4 b3 $1 {The White's plan was too slow, and Black's
counterplay made the position very unclear.} 30. axb3 (30. Ne3 $142 bxc2+ 31.
Nxc2 d5 $1 32. exd5 Rb8 33. Qc3 Qb5 $36 34. Rd1 e4 $1 {[%cal Ge7f6]}) 30...
axb3 31. cxb3 Qxb3 32. Ne3 Ra8 $36 {Black's initiative is actually very
dangerous.} 33. Nd5 $6 {Apparently White still doesn't understand the dangers
of his position.} (33. Qd5 $1 {was the right move} Qa4 34. Rc1 $1 Qa1+ 35. Kc2
Rc8+ 36. Nc4 Qa6 37. Kb1 {and White holds, despite the fact that his position
is still risky.}) 33... Bd8 34. Re3 (34. Nc3 Ba5 $1 {seems unpleasant for White
}) 34... Qa2+ 35. Kc1 Qa1+ 36. Kc2 Rc8+ 37. Rc3 Rb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd8a5]
The defence seems extremely unpleasant for White, and it forces him to expose
his position even more.} 38. b4 (38. Rb3 {loses a pawn after} Qa4 39. Qd3 Rxb3
40. Qxb3 Qxe4+ $17) 38... Ra8 $1 39. Kd3 Qg1 $1 {[%csl Yd4] The invasion of
opponent's position is precisely conducted by Black.} 40. Qe3 Qb1+ 41. Rc2 $2 (
41. Kc4 {would have been the only chance, although it doesn't give many hopes.}
) 41... Ra3+ 42. Nc3 Qxb4 $19 43. Ke2 Ba5 44. Qa7 Qc4+ 45. Kf2 h6 46. Rb2 Qxc3
0-1

