1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg5
Be6 9. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 10. Qd3 Be7 $1 11. Rd1 {White intends to play more solid
with 0-0.} Nd7 12. Nd5 $1 {This should be played now or Black would continue
with ...Nf6 or ...Nb6 and the Nd5 jump would not be a serious worry anymore.}
Bxd5 13. Qxd5 b5 $5 $146 {Giri's novelty, aiming at a quick expansion on the
queenside.} (13... Qc7 {is the most played, also with good results for Black})
14. Bg4 $6 {Trying to disturb Black's development, but as we'll see, White is
the one who will end with badly placed pieces.} (14. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd8c7]} 15.
Qb7 (15. c3 Qc7 16. Qd3 Rad8 {seems equal}) 15... Nf6 $1 16. f3 Re8 $1 {
[%cal Ge7f8,Ge8e7] Played with the idea ...Bf8 followed by ...Re7 when the
b7-queen would be in trouble.}) 14... Nf6 $1 {As we know, it is advisable for
Black to keep his knight on the board.} (14... O-O 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. O-O {
[%csl Yb3,Ge7] it is simply unpleasant for Black}) 15. Qc6+ Kf8 16. Bh3 g6 17.
O-O Kg7 {Black managed to establish a perfect coordination in his camp while
White has a queen and a bishop which are misplaced.} 18. Rfe1 Ra7 $1 {[%cal
Ya7c7] The c8-square is not available, but still Giri finds a nice way to put
a rook on the c-file.} 19. Qc3 (19. Re2 Qb8 {[%cal Ya6a5] is also good for
Black}) 19... Qb6 20. Qe3 {This is practically a confession that the opening
didn't go well for White.} ({Even after} 20. Re2 {White struggles to find a
constructive plan. For example,} Rd8 21. a3 a5 22. g3 b4 23. axb4 axb4 24. Qe1
h5 25. Bg2 Rc8 $15 {[%cal Ya7a2]}) 20... Qxe3 21. Rxe3 a5 {Black is already
playing for an advantage.} 22. a3 (22. g3 a4 23. Nc1 Rc7 24. c3 Rd8 {[%cal
Yd6d5]} 25. Bg2 a3 $1 26. b3 Rdc8 27. Ne2 g5 $1 28. Red3 g4 $15) 22... Rb8 $36
{It is quite impressive how easily Giri managed to neutralize White's play in
the opening and get a nice initiative on the queenside.} 23. c3 (23. g3 a4 24.
Nd2 b4 25. Nc4 bxa3 26. bxa3 Ra6 27. Bf1 Rc6 $15) 23... b4 $1 24. axb4 axb4 25.
c4 Rc7 26. Nd2 {This move is designed to stabilize the queenside by means of
b2-b3.} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5] A very nice idea by Giri. With his last move, he
is planning to improve the bishop.} 27. Ree1 (27. b3 Ra8 {[%cal Ya8a3,Ya8a2]
leaves Black with a great advantage.} 28. Rd3 Nf6 29. f3 Rc6 30. g3 Bd8 $1 $17
{[%cal Yd8b6,Yb6d4]}) 27... Bg5 28. Nf3 (28. b3 Ra8 29. Nf1 Ra3 30. Rb1 Rca7
$17) 28... Bh6 {Black has made the same maneuver with the bishop, but in this
case, it was more successful as it forced new concessions by White.} 29. b3 Ra8
$17 30. Rd5 (30. Ra1 Rxa1 31. Rxa1 Nf6 32. Ra4 (32. Re1 Ra7) 32... Nxe4 33.
Rxb4 Ra7 34. Ra4 Rb7 35. Ra3 Nc5 $19) 30... Ra3 31. Rb1 Nf6 $1 {Precisely
calculated by Giri. Black wins material now.} 32. Rxd6 Nxe4 33. Rd8 (33. Rb6
Nc3 34. Re1 e4 35. Nd4 Bd2 $1 36. Rf1 e3 $1 37. Bg4 exf2+ 38. Kxf2 Re7 {
[%cal Rd2e3]} 39. Kg3 Be3 $19) 33... Rca7 (33... Nc3 34. Re1 Rxb3 $19 {[%csl
Yb4] would be already winning}) 34. Nxe5 Nd2 35. Rxd2 (35. Rd1 Ra1 $1 36. Bg4
Rxd1+ 37. Bxd1 Ra1 $19) 35... Bxd2 $19 {The convertion of the advantage was
not a problem for Giri.} 36. Kf1 Ra1 37. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 38. Ke2 Re1+ $1 {The most
practical.} 39. Kxd2 Rxe5 40. Bd7 Kf6 41. Bc6 Ke7 42. f4 Ra5 43. Kd3 Kd6 44.
Bd5 Kc5 $1 {Avoiding the activation of opponent's king.} 45. Bxf7 Ra3 46. Bg8 (
46. Kc2 Ra2+ 47. Kb1 Rxg2 $19) 46... Rxb3+ 47. Kc2 Re3 48. Bxh7 Re2+ 49. Kb3
Rxg2 50. h4 Rg3+ 51. Kb2 b3 52. Ka3 Kxc4 53. Bg8+ Kc3 54. Bxb3 Kd4 55. Kb4
Rxb3+ $1 {The pawn ending is a trivial win for Black.} 56. Kxb3 0-1

