{What's the best idea for Black in this position?} 37... Rbxc6 $1 (37... Kg7 $6
38. cxb5 axb5 39. f3 $36 {seems to offer some chances for White.}) 38. dxc6
Rxc6 $44 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black seems to have a nice compensation for the
exchange, mainly due to the strong coordination of his pieces and to the
possibility of advancing the central pawns.} 39. Rbb1 $1 Bg5 $1 (39... Bb2 $2
40. Rc2 Bxa3 41. Rb3 $18 {[%csl Ra3]}) 40. Rc2 d5 41. c5 d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]
Black pawns seem very scary.} 42. Rd1 Bf6 $1 {And for this reason, Black
should keep them.} (42... d3 $2 {would be a mistake} 43. Bxd3 $1 exd3 44. Rxd3
$16 {[%cal Yd3d6] and White has the advantage now.}) 43. Rcd2 {White
understands the danger of these pawns, and plays solid.} Nc3 44. Rxd4 $1 (44.
Re1 Kf7 $17 {[%cal Yf7d5,Ga6a5] is simply much better for Black as he can keep
improving his position by bringing the king towards the center. Later on, the
central pawns will start rolling.}) 44... Nxd1 45. Rxd1 {The game followed a
more or less forced path to the draw now.} Bb2 46. Rd8+ (46. Rb1 Bxa3 47. Be2 {
[%csl Ya3] the bishop seems trapped but White cannot win it.} Kf7 48. Kf1 Ke6
49. Ke1 Rc7 50. Kd2 a5 $1 51. bxa5 b4 $17) 46... Kf7 47. Ra8 Bxa3 48. Bxb5 $1
Rc7 (48... axb5 49. Rxa3 $16) 49. Rxa6 Bxb4 50. c6 Ke7 51. Rb6 Bd6 52. Rb7 {
Carlsen,M (2834)-Giri,A (2784) Qatar Masters op 2015 (7) 1/2} *

