1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. f4 $5 {This shows White's intentions of going for a dynamic
battle, with attacking chances and fight for the initiative.} exf4 11. Bxf4 (
11. Rxf4 {is the other option} Nc6 12. Nd5 $5 {the only way of justifying
White's last move} Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne5 14. Rb4 $5 {White aims to cramp Black's
queenside, but this is not enough to achieve the advantage} Qc7 15. a4 Nfd7 16.
a5 Bf6 $11 {and Black is fine as all the important squares on the queenside
are protected and there are no problems to finish the development.}) 11... Nc6
{White has some open lines on the kingside, but the capture exf4 also gives
Black some trumps, like an easier development and the excellent e5-square.} 12.
Qe1 {[%cal Ye1g3,Ya1d1] White plans to follow with Qg3 and Rd1, putting
pressure on d6 and some threats on the kingside. I like Black's next move
because although it is not the main move, it is directed against both plans.} (
12. Kh1 {is also played, then} d5 $1 {gives Black good chances of equalize})
12... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ye8d6,Ge7f6,Ge7h4,Yf6a1] This apparently modest move has
many purposes: It overprotects d6, and at the same time, Qg3 does not seem so
attractive anymore. Besides, Black can improve his dark-squared bishop via f6
and eventually e5.} (12... Ne5 {is the most played, and it is, of course, ok for
Black.}) 13. Rd1 (13. Nd5 Bg5 $1 {this exchange would leave White with a lot
of weaknesses on the dark-squares.} 14. Bg3 Nf6 $1 {It is instructive how the
Black pieces first seemed cramped, and now they become active again.} 15. Nc3
Qe7 16. Rd1 Rad8 {[%cal Yd6d5] Black achieves the d5-advance, and is fine} 17.
Nd2 (17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Nb4 $1) 17... d5 18. exd5 {1/2-1/2 Arnason,
J-Szekely,P/ Tallinn/1983/ (18)}) 13... Bh4 $1 {First diverting the queen from
g3.} 14. Qd2 Bf6 $1 {The bishop aims for the nice square on e5. The pressure
along the a1-h8 diagonal is also not without importance.} 15. Nd5 $5 {Looking
for complications and to take over the initiative.} (15. Bxd6 Nxd6 16. Qxd6
Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Rfe8 {offers nice compensation for Black in form of activity,
for example} 18. Bf3 (18. Nd5 $2 Be5 $19 {[%csl Rd6]}) 18... Be5 19. Rd2 Rac8
20. Rfd1 Bxc3 $1 21. bxc3 Ne5 $15 {[%csl Gc3,Ye5]}) 15... Bxb2 16. c3 (16. Bg5
f6 17. Be3 Be5 18. c3 $13 {would offer White some compensation}) 16... Ba3 {
White will play searching for compensations, but objectively Black is fine and
keeps the extra pawn.} 17. Bg5 f6 (17... Qb8 $6 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nd4 $36) 18.
Be3 Bxd5 $5 {A concrete approach.} (18... b5 19. c4 $1 bxc4 20. Bxc4 $13) 19.
exd5 (19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4e6]} Bc5 $1 21. Rf2 Nc7 22. Qh5 Ne5 $17 {
and Black consolidates the advantage}) 19... Ne5 20. Kh1 (20. Nd4 $5 Qa5 $1 (
20... Nc7 $2 21. Nc2 $1 Bc5 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. d6 Ne6 24. Qd5 Qd7 25. Ne3 $16)
21. Ne6 Rf7 $15) 20... Rc8 21. Nd4 Qa5 $1 {White has some compensation for the
pawn due to the weakness of the e6 square, but his pawns on the queenside also
provide targets for Black.} (21... Nc7 $2 22. Nc2 Bc5 23. Bxc5 dxc5 24. d6 Ne6
25. Ne3 Qd7 26. Nc4 Nxc4 27. Bxc4 $16 {with strong initative for White}) 22.
Nf5 {[%cal Yf5e7]} (22. Ne6 Rf7 {[%csl Rc3]}) 22... Rc7 23. Rb1 Bc5 $6 (23...
b5 $1 24. Rb3 Bc5 25. Bf4 g6 $1 {and Black has a great advantage, for example}
26. Bxe5 dxe5 $1 27. d6 Rd7 28. Qd5+ Kh8 29. Qxc5 gxf5 {[%csl Ra2,Rd6]} 30. Ra3
Qd8 31. Rxa6 Nxd6 32. Bxb5 Nxb5 33. Qxb5 f4 $17 {White regained the pawn but
his pieces are badly placed now}) 24. Bf4 $1 (24. Bxc5 Qxc5 25. a4 g6 $17)
24... Rd7 ({The threat was Bxe5 followed by d6 and Qd5, hence much a better
prophylaxis was} 24... Kh8 $1 25. Nd4 Bxd4 26. cxd4 Qxd2 27. Bxd2 Rc2 $1 28.
Rfd1 Nc4 $17) 25. Nd4 $1 (25. Bg3 b5 $15) 25... Ba7 (25... Bxd4 {was not
possible now} 26. cxd4 $1 Qxd2 27. Bxd2 Nf7 28. Bg4 Rc7 29. Ba5 $36) 26. Ne6
Rff7 27. Rb4 {The position seems complicated now.} g6 (27... Nc7 $2 28. Bxe5
dxe5 29. Nxc7 Qxc7 30. Bg4 $1 $14) 28. Rfb1 f5 29. h3 $2 {Too slow. White
probably missed or underestimated the activation of Black's most passive piece,
the Ne8.} (29. Bg5 $5) 29... Nf6 $1 30. Bxe5 (30. c4 Rfe7 $13) 30... dxe5 31.
c4 Ne4 $1 {Now White has big problems.} 32. Qh6 (32. Qb2 Bd4 $1 33. Nxd4 exd4
34. Bd3 Qc5 $17) (32. Qe1 Bf2 $1 33. Qd1 Nc3 $19) 32... Ng3+ 33. Kh2 Nxe2 34.
Rxb7 $2 (34. R4b2 Nd4 $1 (34... Nc3 35. Rxb7 Nxb1 36. Rxd7 Be3 37. Qxe3 Rxd7
38. Qb3 $1 $40) 35. Ng5 Rfe7 36. Nxh7 Rxh7 37. Qxg6+ Kf8 $19) 34... Rxb7 35.
Rxb7 Qe1 $1 {[%csl Rg1] The last touch.} (35... Rxb7 $4 36. Qf8#) 0-1

