1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3
({Recently, White players started to explore a different move order:} 8. O-O
O-O 9. Qd3 $5 Be6 10. Nd5 $5 Nbd7 11. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Yd2] and the bishop is
apparently better placed on d2 than on e3 for a couple of reasons:} Bxd5 12.
exd5 Nc5 (12... a5 $5 {Hou,Y (2676)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2720) Dortmund SuperGM
43rd 2015 (7) 1/2}) 13. Nxc5 dxc5 14. c4 {[%csl Gd5]} Qc7 15. Rae1 Bd6 16. Qh3
$1 {the first point about 11.Bd2 is the queen has more mobility along the
third rank} Rfe8 17. Bc3 $1 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Yd2c3] and the second is that the
bishop can be improved via c3 to a more promising position on the diagonal.} g6
18. Bd3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3][%cal Gd3h7,Gc3h8] White is well developed and had a
promising position in Nepomniachtchi, I (2751)-Gelfand, B (2724) Zuerich Chess
Challenge 6th 2017 (4) 1-0}) 8... Be6 9. Nd5 $5 Nbd7 $1 10. Qd3 Bxd5 $1 {
Black takes before White is able to reinforce the knight by means of c2-c4.}
11. exd5 Rc8 {Black's chances are on the kingside after the transformation in
the structure, but it is important to take some measures to face White's
advances on the queenside, too.} 12. c4 O-O 13. O-O Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ye7g5,Gf7f5]
Black follows his plan to clear the path in order to advance the f-pawn, but
at the same time, he aims for a typical positional operation in this structure:
exchanging the dark-squared bishop in order to leave his opponent with the bad
bishop, and looking to explore the long-term weaknesses on the dark-squares
with the knights.} 14. Qd2 {[%csl Yg5][%cal Yb3a5,Yb2b4] Preventing Bg5 whilst
simultaneously preparing the queenside expansion with Na5 and b4.} (14. Bg4 {
was played against me, but I found a nice idea now:} e4 $1 {forcing many
exchanges} 15. Qxe4 (15. Qe2 f5 16. Bh3 {[%cal Gb3d4,Gd4e6]} g6 $1 17. Nd4 Ng7
{with a complex position, see the exercise}) 15... Nef6 $1 16. Qd4 Nxg4 17.
Qxg4 Ne5 {[%csl Yc4,Yg4] the point of the 14th move} 18. Qe2 Nxc4 19. Bd4 Re8
$11 {Duran Vega,S (2287) -Quintiliano,R (2441) Continental das Amйricas - El
Salvador (6.12) 0-1 and after the simplifications, Black is ok -}) 14... b6 $5
{A double-edged, ambitious move. It restricts the Nb3 but the drawback is that
the c6-square becomes vulnerable.} (14... f5 {was played by another Najdorf
expert.} 15. f4 g6 16. Na5 exf4 17. Bxf4 Nef6 $1 {[%cal Yf6e4] with good
counterplay for Black - Hovhannisyan,R (2592)-Areshchenko,A (2701) Lake Sevan
Martuni 2014 (7.2) 0-1}) 15. Rac1 $1 a5 16. Na1 $1 {White found a nice way to
improve the knight.} f5 ({Grischuk tried an original plan with} 16... g6 17. b4
$1 (17. Nc2 Ng7 18. Bh6 Re8 {[%cal Yg7f5]} 19. g4 f5 $1 $13) 17... Ng7 (17...
axb4 $2 {would give Black problems after} 18. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Yc2b4,
Yb4c6]} f5 19. Bh6 Rf7 20. Nxb4 Ndf6 21. Nc6 $16) 18. bxa5 bxa5 19. Bd3 Nc5 20.
Bc2 (20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Nb3 Bg5 $1 $132) 20... a4 $5 {[%csl Ya1] with a complex
position, both sides have practical problems here, but Black managed to win
after a complicated fight - Carlsen,M (2853)-Grischuk,A (2771) Sinquefield Cup
3rd 2015 (7) 0-1}) 17. f3 (17. f4 {seems inferior in view of} Nef6 {[%csl Ye4]}
18. Bf3 Nc5 $1 {and e4 is a nice outpost for the knights}) 17... f4 $1 18. Bf2
Bh4 $1 {Mamedyarov shows in an instructive manner how to achieve a nice
position with Black in this line: by exchanging the dark-squared bishops he
obtained a lot of nice squares for the knights.} 19. Bd3 (19. g3 $2 {prevents
the exchange but at a high price} Bg5 20. g4 e4 $1 {[%cal Gd7e5] and Black's
initiative is very strong}) 19... Bxf2+ 20. Qxf2 Nc5 $15 {Black managed to
achieve his strategic ideas and, at the same time, he prevented White's
initiative on the queenside. His position is already easier to play.} 21. Bc2
g6 {Now, it is time to improve the other knight.} 22. Rfe1 ({White has no time
to put the queenside in motion:} 22. b3 Nf6 $1 23. a3 b5 $1 $36) 22... Ng7 23.
Be4 Qd7 24. Nc2 Nf5 25. b3 (25. Bxf5 Qxf5 $19 {[%cal Gc5d3] does not make
White's life easier.}) 25... Kh8 (25... b5 $1 {was already very strong, maybe
Mamedyarov was worried about} 26. cxb5 Qxb5 27. Na3 {[%cal Ya3c4]} Qb4 28. Nc4
{but Black has} Nxe4 29. Rxe4 a4 $17 {with strong pressure on the queenside.}
30. Qb2 axb3 31. axb3 Qc5+ $19 {[%cal Rc5d5]}) 26. Rb1 Ng7 (26... b5 $1 {
would be strong again}) 27. Na3 Nf5 28. Nb5 {White has improved his pieces a
bit, but it is still difficult to see a clear plan for him.} Rf6 29. a3 g5 $6 (
29... a4 $1 {is usually a good move after a3, and was good here, too.} 30. bxa4
(30. b4 Nxe4 31. Rxe4 Ne3 {[%csl Rc4]} 32. Qe2 g5 $36) (30. Bxf5 $2 gxf5 $19 {
[%cal Gc5d3]}) 30... Ne3 $1 $15 {[%csl Ga4,Gc4] and White is in trouble with
many weak pawns}) 30. Nc3 $2 {Georgiadis misses a great chance.} (30. Bxf5 $1
Qxf5 31. b4 $1 {would give nice chances for White, for example} Nd3 $2 (31...
Nd7 $142 32. Qe2 $13) 32. Qc2 $1 Nxe1 33. Qxf5 Rxf5 34. Nxd6 $16 {[%csl Rc8,
Rf5] and White regains the material with advantage}) 30... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Yd4]
The knight is very strong on d4 and White's position becomes unpleasant.} 31.
b4 (31. Bc2 g4 {Black has a crushing attack, for example} 32. b4 gxf3 $1 33.
bxc5 Rg8 $19) 31... axb4 32. Rxb4 (32. axb4 Nxe4 33. Nxe4 Rg6 34. Rbc1 g4 $40 {
and the attack is too strong again}) 32... g4 $40 {The attack comes with full
force.} 33. Qh4 $6 (33. Nb5 {was a better try, but after} Nxb5 34. Rxb5 Rg8 {
White's position remains very difficult.}) 33... Nxe4 34. Nxe4 Rg6 35. fxg4 Nc2
$19 36. Rxb6 Nxe1 37. Nf6 (37. Qxe1 Qa7 $1 38. Qf2 Rxc4 $19) 37... Qg7 38. Rxd6
Rh6 39. Qxe1 Rxf6 0-1

