1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd2 {There are some lines in which White plays in a slow
way looking for a small advantage based on easier play and trying to slowly
restrict Black.} (10. a4 {allows} Nc6 {[%csl Gb4] which can be a better
development for the knight, seen in many similar positions} 11. Bf3 Na5 $1 12.
Nxa5 Qxa5 13. Qd2 {[%cal Yc3d5]} Rfc8 $1 {and Black is fine} 14. Rfd1 (14. Nd5
$6 Qxd2 15. Nxe7+ Kf8 16. Bxd2 Rxc2 $1 17. Bc3 Kxe7 18. Bd1 Rxc3 $1 19. bxc3
Nxe4 $17) 14... Kf8 $1 {preventing Nd5} 15. Qc1 Rc4 $1 16. Rd3 Rac8 {and Black
is at least ok - Kamsky,G (2705)-Gelfand,B (2733) Wch Candidates final 2007 (2.
1) 1/2}) 10... Nbd7 11. a4 {When Black is deprived of the Nc6-b4 idea, White
advances his a-pawn.} Rc8 12. a5 {[%csl Ga5] Black should be careful in such
positions, as White plays with an easier game and a bit more space. It is
important to not try to do anything drastically but instead to keep improving
the pieces.} Re8 13. Rfd1 ({In a recent game White played} 13. Bf3 {and the
continuation was very instructive:} h6 14. Nc1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc1d3,Gd3b4]}
Nh7 $1 {a very nice idea} 15. g3 Bg5 $1 16. Nd3 (16. Qxd6 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Ng5 18.
Bg2 Nf6 $1 {gives Black a lot of activity for the pawn.} 19. Qxd8 Rexd8 20. h4
Nh3+ 21. Kh2 Rd2 $1 $36 {[%cal Gf6g4]}) 16... Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6d4] now
the knight is also improved} 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Qxg5 hxg5 $1 19. Rfd1 Nc6 20.
Ne2 g4 $1 21. Bg2 Ng5 $15 {and Black obtained a clear advantage - Zherebukh,Y 
(2633)-Xiong,J (2640) St Louis Spring A 2018 (1.4) 0-1}) 13... h6 14. Nc1 {
[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc1d3,Yd3b4] A typical plan for White is to play Nd3-b4 trying
to increase the control over d5.} (14. f3 {is the most solid, but leads to
positions in which both sides have difficulties to make progress.} Qc7 15. Nc1
Bf8 16. Bf1 (16. Nd3 d5 $1 $36) 16... Red8 17. Qe1 Qc6 {[%cal Yd6d5]} 18. Qd2
Qc7 $11 {Nakamura,H (2772) -Korobov,A (2720) FIDE World Cup 2013 (4.1) 1/2})
14... Qc7 15. Bf3 {It is necessary to follow the plan.} (15. Nd3 d5 $1 {
is a bit complicated, but Black manages to equalize.} 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5
Bxd5 18. Nxe5 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Ye5]} 19. Ng4 $5 Qxc2 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Qxd5
Qxe2 22. Rd2 Qc4 23. Qxb7 Rb8 $11 {[%csl Yb2]}) 15... b5 $1 16. axb6 (16. Nd3 {
again is bad due to} d5 $1 {although this time it is a true pawn sacrifice} 17.
exd5 Bf5 {[%cal Yb5b4,Ge5e4]} 18. Ne1 Bd6 19. g3 Qb7 $44 {[%cal Ye5e4,Gd7c5,
Yd6b4,Ge8d8] and the fact that Black has many different ideas in this position
says everything about his compensation.}) 16... Nxb6 {[%cal Yb6c4] Black's
active idea was very strong, but it is important to understand why: White has
lost the coordination between his pieces in the last moves: first the knight
went back, cutting the communication between the rooks, and then the bishop
left the e2-square, leaving c4 unprotected. Black players should understand
that after b5-axb6 it is necessary to play for the initiative, as otherwise,
White would achieve a favorable endgame.} 17. Be2 $6 (17. Bxb6 $142 Qxb6 18.
N1e2 Rc6 $11 {[%cal Ye8c8]}) 17... Nc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 $15 {Black position seems
already easier to play.} 19. Qe1 (19. f3 {see the exercise}) 19... Qb7 $1 {
[%csl Yb2,Ye4] A consistent way to improve the position.} 20. b3 Be6 21. f3 d5
$1 $36 {This advance activates the bishop pair as well as all Black's pieces,
putting White under unpleasant pressure.} 22. exd5 Bxd5 (22... Nxd5 23. Nxd5
Bxd5 24. Qe2 {seems less dangerous for White}) 23. Nd3 (23. Nxd5 Nxd5 $19 {
[%csl Yc2][%cal Gd5e3,Re7c5] with undefendable threats}) 23... e4 $1 {
Naturally, opening new lines is a good idea for Black.} 24. fxe4 Bxe4 25. Nxe4
Nxe4 {[%csl Gc2] It seems already difficult for White to avoid material losses.
} 26. Qa5 ({For example} 26. Rac1 Nc3 27. Rd2 Bg5 $19) 26... Bf6 $1 27. Qxa6
Qxa6 28. Rxa6 Nc3 29. Re1 Rxe3 $1 30. Rxe3 Bd4 31. Kf2 Re8 $19 32. b4 Rxe3 33.
Kf1 Ne4 34. g3 Nd2+ 35. Kg2 Re2+ 36. Kh3 Nf1 37. Kg4 Rxc2 38. Rd6 Nxh2+ 39. Kf4
Rc4 40. Rd8+ Kh7 41. Rd7 Bc3+ 0-1

