1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {The Najdorf is the most
popular Sicilian played in tournaments, and I consider it the most reliable
option in the Sicilian universe (although the Taimanov has proven its value
too, and also the Accelerated Dragon in a reduced number of tests). It
promises an active game for Black and real chances of playing for a win.
Black's ideas are generally based on quick development and the search for
counterplay on the queenside and center, aiming to take the initiative as early
as possible. The main practical problem for Black, however, is that White has
a really wide range of options to face the Najdorf. White can even avoid an
open and sharp battle for the initiative and instead go for more solid and
positional lines, which can prove a problem for aggressive Black players. It
means that if you want to develop a deep knowledge about the Sicilian Najdorf
in order to use this opening as a weapon in your repertoire, it is necessary
to not only be aware of long and sharp theoretical lines, but also of
positional ideas, typical maneuvres and structures, developing a good
strategic understanding about them. These positional lines will be the subject
of our first database dedicated to the Sicilian Najdorf.} 6. Be2 ({This
database will also cover} 6. a4 $5 g6) ({and} 6. g3 e5) ({as well as} 6. Be3 {
but the lines in which after} e5 {White plays} 7. Nf3 {going for a positional
battle instead of the sharp English Attack}) 6... e5 {[%csl Gd5] The typical
Najdorf structures arise after this advance, which gives more freedom for
Black's development and the fight for space in the center, but the price is
the weakening of the d5-square which becomes a very important strategic point.
Both sides usually develop their plans based around keeping control of the d5
square. This structure will occur in many different lines, and we will see how
to deal with it in general terms as well as in specific cases. Enjoy it!} *

