this is always a useful move.} 15. Ra3 $5 {White keeps his ideas open.} (15.
Ra4 {was another option, but after} Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%cal Gd7c5] White has
to expect Nc5 at some point.}) 15... Nd7 $1 {Black exchanges the bishop, but
in return obtains more freedom for his pieces in a slightly cramped position.}
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Kg8 18. Rd2 {[%cal Yc3d5] White prepares the jump to d5
after which the rook on a4 could come into the game via the third rank.} Qc5 $1
{Again this exchange is very precise.} 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 {
[%cal Gc2c4,Gb2b4] White hopes to advance his b and c pawns in order to cramp
Black's queenside and to try to exploit it in the endgames. Nepo solves this
task in a very practical way.} b5 $5 22. axb6 Nxb6 23. Rxa6 Nxd5 {From my
experience, appearances in this endgame can be deceptive. Despite White having
