1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 {This is another
line that has the reputation of being a solid option for White and is played
by many strong players like Carlsen, Anand, MVL, etc.} e5 {[%csl Gd5] This is
how we start to analyze this structure, very typical of Najdorf positions.
Black is fighting for space in the center and for more freedom to develop his
pieces. In this particular position, he also blocks the diagonal for the Bg2 in
advance. As nothing is perfect, we now have the problem of the d5-square,
which creates the main positional battle in this chapter and in the next ones.}
7. Nb3 {Let's start with this retreat that is the second most played.} (7. Nde2
{is the main line, see chapter 4.}) (7. Nf3 $5 {was also tested in recent
games, see chapter 3.}) ({but} 7. Nf5 $6 {is bad in view of} d5 $1 8. Bg5 d4 9.
Bxf6 gxf6 $1 10. Nb1 Bxf5 11. exf5 Qd5 12. Rg1 Nc6 $15) 7... Be7 {It is good to keep the light-squared bishop flexible, as it can prove more useful to develop
it to b7 in certain positions.} ({I used to play} 7... Nbd7 {first but a
tournament game changed my mind:} 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] the start of a nice
plan, the first step is to contain the initiative on the queenside. As this
move also threatens a5, Black is forced to answer} b6 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O Be7
11. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gd2c4,Gc4e3] another point behind 8.a4 is that
White is able now to maneuver the knight to e3 via c4} Rc8 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. Rd1
$1 {[%cal Yd2f1,Yf1e3] the knight finds another route to e3} O-O $6 {as it
happens in this structure, one inaccuracy is enough to get an unpleasant
position} ({correct was} 13... Nc5 14. Nf1 Ne6 $1 {[%cal Ge6d4] and Black has
sufficient counterplay with his knight also coming to d4} 15. Ne3 Nd4 16. Qd3
O-O 17. Bd2 Qd7 $13 {[%cal Yb6b5] and it is not so easy to make progress for
White}) 14. Nf1 Rfe8 $6 (14... Nc5 $5 15. Bg5 $1 {forces favourable exchanges
for White} Ne6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne3 Nd4 18. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Gd5] White not
only has full control over d5 here but soon the Nd4 will be driven out of
this square, giving White an indisputable advantage}) 15. Ne3 $14 {[%csl Gd5]
although I made normal developing moves, I realized that my position was
already unpleasant due to the firm control of White over d5. White won with a nice technique in Valerga, D (2451) -Quintiliano Pinto, R (2469) Mercosur Cup
21st 2017 (3) 1-0}) 8. Bg2 (8. a4 {is not so effective now because Black has
kept his knight on b8, so he can arrange the pieces in a different (better)
way:} Nc6 $1 9. Bg2 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Yb8c6,Yc6b4] This is an important
idea to remember in this line, when White slightly commits his queenside by
playing a4: the knight can't be easily driven out of b4, and the first point is
that it helps Black to control d5.} 10. Bg5 Be6 $1 {in the notes to the 7th
move, Black's mistake was to castle too early which allowed White quick
mobilization of his forces to control d5. This time, however, Black
concentrates his efforts to protect this square as much as possible before
castling} 11. O-O Rc8 $1 {the second point of having the knight on b4 is that
Black exerts pressure against c2, which is reinforced by this last move and
prevents Nd5 or other knight's moves in order to play c2-c3} 12. a5 {[%cal
Ya1a4]} Qd7 $1 {this secures the position of the Nb4 by tactical means. This
practically ends White's hopes of playing for an advantage as the Black pieces
are very well coordinated} 13. Nc1 (13. Ra4 $2 Nxc2 $1 14. Qxc2 Qxa4 $19 {
[%cal Yc8c2] is the point}) 13... O-O 14. Nd3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 {Black has no
problems and even started to play for advantage after} h6 $1 {Guo,A (2219)
-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2451) SPICE Cup Open 2017 2017 (4.18) 0-1}) 8... O-O 9.
O-O b5 $5 {This move used to be considered dubious, but some recent games have
changed this evaluation.} (9... Be6 {is the most played} 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Re1 {
[%cal Yb3d2,Yd2f1,Yf1e3] with the same idea of maneuvering the knight,
although in those lines Black has also his ideas, that give him good chances})
10. a4 $1 {This move is usually good to counter early advances on queenside by
Black.} (10. Nd5 {direct is harmless, as Black's queenside was not commited}
Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Ra7 12. Be3 Be6 13. Qd2 Ra8 14. a4 (14. f4 a5 $1 15. f5 Bc4 16.
Rfe1 Nd7 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Nc1 {[%cal Yb2b3]} f6 $11 {Lupulescu,C (2627)-Palac,
M (2546) 19th ch-EUR Indiv 2018 2018 (11.33) 1/2-1/2}) (14. Na5 $5 Qc7 {
[%cal Gb8c6]}) 14... Nc6 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Ra1 Qb7 {[%cal Yf8a8]
and Black is fine - Naiditsch,A (2710) -Vidit,S (2693) ESP-chT CECLUB Honor
2017 (6.2) 1/2-1/2}) ({Sticking to the plan of transferring the knight to e3
is bad for White now:} 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Nf1 b4 $1 {and after} 13.
Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 {[%csl Yd5] Black has no worries about neither the d5-square
nor the d6-pawn anymore and is free to begin his own play on the kingside.
This is why White should always keep d5 under control in order to occupy it
with a piece, not with a pawn.} f5) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Ra7 13. Be3
Be6 $1 {An important intermediate move.} (13... Rd7 $2 14. Na5 $1 $16) 14. Qd3
{The best move to make Black's development harder.} (14. Qd2 {[%csl Yb4] may
look most logical, but in fact after} Rb7 {the a6-pawn is not under attack,
which means that Black has an easier task to bring the Nb8 into the game} 15.
a5 {trying to keep the queenside pawns separated now.} (15. f4 Nd7 $1 {for
example, this wouldn't be possible with the queen on d3}) (15. Rfd1 Qc7 16.
Rac1 Nd7 17. Bf1 Ra8 18. c4 a5 $11 {Adams, M (2729)-Alekseev,E (2716) ESP-chT
finals 2007 (2) 1/2-1/2}) {I like the still untested} 15... Qc8 $5 $146 {
[%csl Ya6] the idea is to keep the a6-pawn protected for while, as after the
knight leaves b8, White's idea is to press a6, with Bf1 or Qd3} 16. Rfc1 (16.
Ra4 {can give the initiative to Black} Nd7 $1 17. Rc1 Re8 $1 18. Rxb4 Rxb4 19.
Qxb4 d5 $1 20. Qa4 d4 21. Bd2 Qb7 $44 {[%cal Yd7f6,Ge6d7,Gd7c6,Ge8c8] with
sufficient compensation for Black in form of active play}) 16... Qc6 $1 17. f4
(17. Qd3 Nd7 18. Bf1 Rb5 $1 {and Black is fine} 19. c3 $5 bxc3 $1 20. Rxc3 Qb7
21. Nd2 Nc5 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. b3 Rd8 24. Qc2 Rb4 25. Bc4 Qc6 $11 {Black is
active enough to keep the balance}) 17... Nd7 18. c4 $5 {[%cal Yf4f5]} f6 $1 {
keeping the position closed on the queenside seems safer for Black} (18... bxc3
19. Rxc3 Qb5 20. Bf1 {[%csl Ga6] leads to some complications, although the
evaluation is not clear}) 19. Qe2 {[%cal Yb3d2] White can start some maneuvers
now with the intention of improving the Nb3, eventually jumping to e3 and
finally to d5, but it is very instructive to see that Black has always a way
to prevent this plan} Nc5 20. Nd2 ({the first natural attempt would be} 20.
Bxc5 dxc5 21. f5 Bf7 22. Nd2 {[%cal Yd2f1,Yf1e3,Ye3d5] but Black is just in
time to play} Rd8 23. Nf1 Rbd7 $1 {[%csl Yd2]} 24. b3 Rd3 25. Rd1 $5 Rxd1 26.
Rxd1 Rxd1 27. Qxd1 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6d4] basically forcing the trade of the
queens, and after} 28. Qxd6 Bxd6 $17 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gd6c7] not only did the
White plan fails, he is also about to lose the a-pawn.}) 20... Bf7 21. b3 Rd8
22. f5 {again, apparently White has fixed the structure according to his
wishes, but Black is also very solid.} Rbb8 23. Qd1 {the last detail before
the knight maneuver is to transfer the queen to c2 in order to protect both e4
and b3. But Black has a strong regroupment in mind, too} Qb7 24. Qc2 Be8 $1 {
[%cal Ge8c6]} 25. Bf2 Bc6 26. Re1 {and after} g6 $1 $36 {Black is even playing
for the initiative, as the White pawns provide some points of contact in the
center and on the kingside.}) 14... Ra8 $5 {Grischuk's move. The rook goes
back to its initial square, but Black can develop the knight without problems.}
({I think the text is safer than the mostly played} 14... Rb7 {I don't like
this move. The reason is an instructive game of Ponomariov that went:} 15. Rfc1
$1 Qc7 16. c3 $1 {a very strong move that opens the queenside where Black has
some development problems.} Bc4 (16... Bxb3 $2 17. cxb4 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gd3b3]
}) 17. Qc2 Be6 18. Qd1 Qd8 19. Bf1 $1 bxc3 20. Rxc3 Bg5 $2 {a bad exchange,
even though trading the bad bishop is usually advisable.} 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. Bc4
$1 Bxc4 23. Rxc4 Nd7 24. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Ga6,Gd6] and Black had problems with
the weak pawns - Ponomariov,R (2734) -Safarli,E (2620) Istanbul ol (Men) 40th
2012 (10.2) 1-0}) 15. f4 {White creates tension in the center, trying to
provoke some concession in Black's center.} (15. Rfc1 {was played once, but it
is not dangerous for Black now} Nd7 16. f4 {Fluvia Poyatos, J (2445)-Smith, T 
(2193) Barbera del Valles op 36th 2013 (8) 1-0} a5 17. f5 Bxb3 18. Qxb3 Bg5 $1
{[%csl Gd7,Yg2] and Black obtains a nice position because he got a better
minor piece.} 19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. Rd1 Rfd8 $1 {[%cal Yd7c5] Black can even
sacrifice the pawn, as his position will be very active in the end} 21. Rxd6 $6
Nc5 22. Qd5 Rxd6 23. Qxa8+ Qd8 $1 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $44) (15. a5 {[%csl Ra6]
fixing a6 also seems natural. But since a6 is protected, Black can simply
continue with} Nd7 {[%cal Yd7c5]} 16. Nd2 $5 {avoiding the forced exchanges
with Nc5} Qc7 17. Rfc1 {Marinkovic,I (2444)-Arsovic,G (2483) Serbia-chT
Zlatibor 2006 (5) 1-0} Rfc8 $11) (15. Nd2 {[%cal Yd2c4]} Qc7 16. Rfc1 Nd7 17.
c3 {Black equalized easily now with} Nc5 $1 18. cxb4 Nxd3 19. Rxc7 Bd8 20. Rc3
Nxb4 21. Nc4 Rc8 $1 {Kollars, D (2429)-Teplyi, I (2433) Aarhus Chess House 2016 
(3) 1/2-1/2} 22. Nxd6 $6 Rxc3 23. bxc3 Nc2 24. Rb1 Nxe3 25. fxe3 Be7 26. Nf5
Ba3 $15 27. Rb6 $2 g6 28. Nh4 Bc5 $17) 15... Qc7 16. Nd2 (16. Rfc1 Rc8 $1 {
prevents the c3 idea}) 16... a5 $1 {Now the queenside pawns are safe.} 17. Rf2
{This was played twice. White intends to place the other rook on c1 and keep
some pressure on the f-file.} (17. f5 Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 17... f6 {
Grischuk keeps playing solidly, first on the queenside and now in the centre.}
18. f5 {I don't think White needs to release the tension. This seems good for
Black as his position becomes very solid in the centre now.} (18. Bh3 $5 Bf7 $1
(18... Bxh3 $2 19. Qd5+ {[%csl Ra8]}) 19. Rc1 Na6 $11) 18... Bf7 19. Rc1 Na6
$11 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black is very solid and has his own plans, too, such as Nc5
or preparing the advance d6-d5. The only plan for White is to open the c-file
by means of c3. However, since this pawn push would mean creating some
weaknesses in his own camp, it is not an easy decision. This is what more or
less happened in Hou, Y (2652)-Grischuk, A (2750) Moscow FIDE GP 2017 (5) 0-1,
with a favorable ending for Black.} *

