{[%evp 0,32,37,20,49,58,72,61,61,44,44,42,47,2,2,-4,9,17,12,-9,58,-2,7,-53,45,
41,12,3,11,-13,-6,-31,-50,-37,-64]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nf3 $5 {This started to be played recently, in order to
create new challenges for Black. The main idea is to maneuver the knight to f5
via h4, trying to put some pressure on the kingside.} Be7 8. Bg2 ({White can
accelerate his plan and play} 8. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Yh4f5]} O-O 9. Nf5 (9. Bg2 g6 $1
{preventing the idea} 10. a4 (10. Bh6 {does not seem good, as after} Re8 {
White is not able to prevent b5 because he should stop Ng4 in the first place}
11. h3 b5 $1 12. a3 Bb7 {and Black's position looks at least playable, after}
13. Qd2 {[%cal Gh4f5] ; Safarli, E (2676)-Mansner,H (2278) 34th ECC Open 2018
2018 (1.3) 1-0} Nfd7 $1 {[%csl Yg5] since Nf5 was possible for tactical
reasons, it is important to protect the g5-square.} 14. Nf3 Nb6 15. O-O N8d7
16. Rad1 Rc8 $132 {and Black's pieces seem even better placed from the opening}
) (10. O-O {Nepomniachtchi, I (2767) -Volokitin, A (2649) Wch Blitz Doha blitz
2016 (1) 1-0} b5 $5 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Ra7 14. Be3 Be6 15. Qd2 Rb7
16. Nf3 {this structure is pretty much the same as that one analyzed in
chapter 2. Compared to that chapter, however, the knight is probably worse
placed on f3 than on b3.} Nc6 17. Rfd1 b3 $1 18. c3 Na5 $132 {[%csl Gc4]})
10... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gb4] as we already know, after a4 the b4-square becomes
attractive for the knight} 11. O-O Bd7 $5 {a very interesting and subtle move
which was probably home preparation by Team Nepomniachtchi. At first sight,
this square may look unnatural, but the bishop is less exposed than on e6:
f4-ideas for White are not so dangerous, neither is Nf3-g5, and Black is able
to take with the knight in response to an eventual Nd5.} (11... Bg4 {forced
simplifications and was also enough to equalize} 12. Nf3 Nd4 13. Be3 Nxf3+ 14.
Bxf3 Be6 $1 {keeping White's bad bishop on the board} 15. a5 Rc8 16. Bg2 Rc4
17. Qd3 Qc8 $11 {Motylev,A (2680)-Kokarev,D (2620) RUS-ch Higher League 70th
2017 (9) 1/2-1/2}) 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Nf3 Na5 {Black's play is natural and sound,
and it is clear that White failed to get any advantage from the opening} 14. h3
Re8 15. Qd3 Qc7 16. Qe3 (16. Bg5 Nc4 17. Bxf6 $2 Nxb2 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc7c3]})
16... b5 $36 {Oparin,G (2609)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2768) 71st ch-RUS 2018 2018 (9.
2) 0-1}) 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 {Kovalev,V (2664)-Guramishvili, S (2378) chess.com
IoM Masters 2018 (1.27) 1-0 White has accomplished the main plan, but he
wasted a lot of time doing it, so Black can take the initiative in the centre:}
d5 $1 11. Bg2 (11. Bg5 Nbd7 {is harmless}) 11... d4 $1 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4
Qc7 {despite White having the bishop pair, Black is fine, for example:} 14. O-O
Nd7 15. Re1 (15. Bg2 Rac8 {[%csl Yc2]}) 15... Rfe8 16. Bd2 Nf6 17. Bd3 Bf8 $11)
8... O-O 9. O-O (9. Nh4 g6 $1 {transposes to Oparin-Nepomniachtchi}) (9. a4 {
prevents b5, but allows Black to protect the d5-square better with the already
known idea} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gb4]} 10. O-O Be6 11. Nh4 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} 12. Nf5
Bxf5 13. exf5 d5 14. Bg5 e4 15. a5 $1 {[%cal Ya1a4] ;Ponkratov,P (2601)-Sarana,
A (2587) TCh-RUS Premier 2018 2018 (8.2) 1/2-1/2} Rc8 16. Ra4 {[%cal Yg5f6]} b5
$1 {and Black gets strong counterplay} 17. axb6 Qxb6 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxd5
Nxd5 20. Qxd5 e3 $1 $132) 9... b5 $1 {Whenever possible, this move is a good
way for Black's to fight for the control over the d5-square and to look for
counterplay on the queenside.} 10. Nd5 {This was played in the most recent
game between GMs, but White has tried other moves too.} (10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Nh4
h6 $1 12. Be3 (12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nf5 Be6 14. Ne3 b4 $1 {is an improved version
of the game for Black} 15. Ncd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Rc8 $132) 12... Nb6
13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Nf5 Bxf5 $6 {this apparently gives an easier game for White}
(14... Ra7 15. Ne3 Be6 {[%cal Yf8c8,Ya7c7] looks like a better option.}) 15.
exf5 Rac8 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 b4 $1 18. Re1 Rc5 {[%cal Yb6c7] I think such
positions are easier to play for White in practice, but Black managed to get
enough counterplay in Balogh,C (2638)-Kanakaris,G (2359) GRE-chT 45th 2017 (2.
9) 1/2-1/2}) (10. a4 b4 11. Nd5 {this position occured in five games in
tournament practice, but} a5 $146 {was not played yet. The point is to make
the pawns safe on the queenside, because the absence of the Nb3 tells in
Black's favour, for example} 12. Nh4 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Ra6 $1 {the rook also
protects d6 using the third rank now} 14. Nf5 Be6 15. Qd3 Rc6 $1 16. Rd1 g6 17.
Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Bh6 Rfc8 $132) 10... Bb7 {Black aims to get pressure against
White's center.} (10... Nbd7 {would be more precise, in my opinion} 11. Nxe7+ (
11. Nh4 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Nb6 {[%csl Yh4]}) 11... Qxe7 12. Nh4 Nc5 13. Re1 (13. Nf5
Bxf5 14. exf5 d5 $132) 13... g6 14. Bg5 Rd8 15. Qf3 Kg7 {[%cal Yc5e6,Gc8b7]
and Black is ok}) 11. Nxe7+ {Strategically speaking, trading the knight for
the bad-bishop seems an improvement for Black.} (11. Nxf6+ {would have made
more sense} Bxf6 12. Re1 Be7 13. Nd2 {[%cal Yd2f1,Yf1e3] and the fight for d5
goes on, although Black comes in time to organize the pieces and gets a nice
position} Nd7 14. Nf1 Nc5 $1 {forcing White to waste some time defending e4
before continuing the knight's maneuver.} 15. c3 (15. f3 {seems
anti-positional as blockades the bishop and weakens the dark-squares}) 15...
Qd7 16. Qc2 f5 $1 {and Black is actually already better} 17. exf5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2
Rxf5 $36 {[%cal Gd7b7,Ya8f8]}) 11... Qxe7 12. Nh4 Qe6 $1 {A nice and
multi-purpose move, anticipating Nf5, preventing the pin and preparing d6-d5.}
13. Re1 (13. Nf5 d5 $1 {gives active play for Black}) 13... Nbd7 {Black's
development is natural and good.} 14. Qe2 Rac8 15. c3 Rc4 $1 16. f3 (16. Qc2 b4
$36) 16... d5 $1 $36 {And Black took the initiative in Hammer,J (2662)-Hansen,
E (2629) St Louis Fall A 2018 2018 (1.1) 0-1} *

