14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 {Black is ok due to his better development, his
pieces can combine attack and defense with moves like Nc4, for example} 16.
O-O-O b4 $1 17. Nd5 $6 (17. Ne2 $142 Rfd8 18. b3 a5 19. Kb2 Kf8 $11 {[%cal
Yf8e7]}) 17... Nxd5 $1 18. exd5 Bf5 {[%csl Yc2]} 19. f4 Rfc8 20. Rd2 Rc5 {
[%cal Ya8c8] and Black is already playing for the win in this endgame -
Karjakin,S (2781)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2796) Norway Chess 5th 2017 (9) 1/2-1/2})
(13. a4 {is pointless now} b4 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 {Gu,T (2171)
-Wang Jue (2365) ch-CHN Women 2018 2018 (10.3) 0-1} Bg4 $1 {and Black is fine})
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black has no problems here.} 15. a4 b4 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17.
Qxd5 Be6 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is very interesting, as it gives Black
sufficient activity, open lines and strong pressure against c2. White has
problems to keep the material and find good squares for his pieces.} 18. Qxd6
a5 19. Qb6 ({it is not so easy to keep the pawn:} 19. Qd2 Rac8 20. Rac1 Rfd8
