{[%evp 0,42,15,38,62,45,72,61,61,44,44,29,43,21,48,20,34,15,11,11,16,12,11,1,6,
-7,-7,-7,3,-34,-27,-27,-17,-12,-6,-6,18,18,4,4,3,2,1,8,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nf3 $5 {Like mentioned in
chapter 4, and we will see in the next databases, White has tried many
different ideas against the Najdorf recently, looking for fertile ground for
new ideas. After a couple of nice wins by Carlsen, this move gained some
popularity among GMs, instead of the main and classical retreat to b3. There
are some subtle differences that White can explore in his fight for d5.} Be7 (
7... h6 {prevents Bg5, but White can maneuver now to get control over d5:} 8.
Nd2 $1 Be6 (8... b5 {is premature due to} 9. a4 $1 b4 10. Nd5 $1 {and Black
has problems with his queenside} Nxd5 11. exd5 {[%cal Ya4a5,Gd2c4] Black
should accept the unpleasant grip on the queenside after Nc4-a5, as} a5 $2 12.
Bb5+ Bd7 13. Nc4 $16 {gives a great advantage to White}) 9. Nc4 {[%csl Gd5]
[%cal Yc4e3]} Qc7 ({Korobov tried a different idea with} 9... Nc6 {Vachier
Lagrave,M (2789) -Korobov,A (2652) World Blitz 2017 blitz 2017 (9.4) 1-0} 10.
Be3 $1 {[%csl Gb6] would be already unpleasant for Black} b5 11. Nb6 Rb8 12.
Nbd5 $14 {[%cal Ya2a4]}) 10. Nd5 $1 {this was played only once and it was back
in 1964(!) but it forces a transformation in the pawn structure that seems
good for White} Bxd5 (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. a4 $1 {[%cal Ya4a5]}) 11.
exd5 Nbd7 (11... b5 {only helps White} 12. Ne3 Nbd7 13. a4 $1 $36) 12. O-O Be7
{Bannik,A-Sakharov, Y UKR-ch33 Final 1964 (10) 1/2-1/2} 13. a4 O-O 14. a5 $14 {
[%csl Gd6][%cal Yf2f4,Ya1a3] and White's position is obviously easier: he has
cramped Black's queenside, the Nc4 keeps d6 under pressure and he can open
lines with f4 or bring the rook to the game via a3}) 8. Bg5 {Compared to the
variation analyzed in chapter 10, White can play this move whilst saving a
tempo now. Exchanging the dark-squared bishop for the knight is one of the
typical operations in such structures: mathematically speaking, White trades
off one of the opponent's pieces which can control d5, for one of his own
pieces that never could occupy that square, in order to have more pieces
available in the fight for the d5-square.} Be6 {This move has not scored so
well, but I do not think the opening is the reason for that. Besides, it is
Ding Liren's move, which means that it is at least reliable!} (8... Nbd7 {
this is another set-up that seems ok for Black too. It is how Vachier Lagrave,
another Najdor's expert, meets this variation. I recommend Black players
analyze it deeper if you want to keep pieces on the board in more complex
positions, instead of our main line.} 9. a4 $1 {preventing the active
development by b5-Bb7} h6 $1 {this prevents White from completing his ideal
development.} 10. Be3 (10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bb3 O-O 13. O-O Rc8 14.
Qe2 Qa5 $11 {Popovic,D (2517)-Karjakin,S (2760) 43rd Olympiad 2018 2018 (7.10)
1/2-1/2}) 10... Ng4 $1 {forcing the bishop to retreat again.} 11. Bc1 Ngf6 12.
O-O O-O {and White has no easy way to continue his development. The game went}
13. b3 (13. h3 Nc5 14. Nd2 Be6 {[%cal Yd6d5]}) 13... Nc5 14. Nd2 Be6 15. Bb2
Rc8 {and Black is well developed, White was not able to make progress in Giri,
A (2782)-Grischuk,A (2766) GCT Rapid YourNextMove rapid 2018 (9.5) 1/2-1/2}) 9.
Bxf6 $1 {White should make this exchange before Black brings the other knight
to d7, in order to make Black lose some tempi to organize his pieces again.} (
9. O-O Nbd7 {and Black's development is simple}) 9... Bxf6 10. O-O {In recent
games, White has tried to improve his position, instead of immediately putting
the knight on d5.} (10. Nd5 {was the most played when the line appeared in
recent tournament practice} Nd7 11. O-O ({White can rush to improve his
control over d5 with} 11. Bc4 {Mareco,S (2643)-Salinas Herrera,P (2463)
American Continental TB rapid 2018 (4.3) 0-1 but after} Rc8 12. Qe2 Nb6 $1 {
[%csl Yc4,Yd5] he is not able to keep a stable control of the central squares}
13. Nxb6 Qxb6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. c3 O-O 16. O-O {and Black is even playing for
an advantage after} d5 $5 $36 {[%cal Yc8c4]}) 11... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Yc4] a very
important move preventing Bc4 that would reinforce White's control over d5. I
think this quick mobilization on the queenside is enough to solve Black's
opening tasks.} 12. Re1 O-O 13. c3 Be7 14. Bf1 Nf6 $1 {and now Black solves
the problem of d5} 15. Qb3 Nxd5 16. exd5 Bg4 $1 17. Nd2 (17. Qxb7 $2 Bxf3 18.
gxf3 a5 $15 {[%csl Gg1] seems risky for White}) 17... Rb8 {the structure has
changed and Black got nice chances due to the bishop pair and the mobile
kingside pawns that allowed him to take the initiative after} 18. a4 Qa5 19. Qc4
Bh5 20. b4 Qd8 21. a5 f5 $132 {Tari,A (2578)-Ding Liren (2772) 33rd ECC Open
2017 2017 (3.9) 0-1}) (10. Qd2 $5 {has been tried in a few recent games. Black
cannot play Nd7 now and, at the same time, White prepares to increase the
pressure putting one rook on d1.} O-O 11. O-O (11. Rd1 Qb6 $1 $132) 11... Qc7
12. Rfd1 Be7 {and even after} 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Nd7 {White had no
advantage.} 15. Nd2 b5 $5 16. c4 b4 $1 {[%cal Yd7c5] Black has the nice square
c5 to his knight, or even Nf6 if he wants to keep d5 guarded. Advancing the
queenside pawns is another possible idea, which gave Black an active
counterplay in Van Foreest, J (2617)-Fedoseev, V (2713) Van Foreest-Fedoseev m
2018 (6) 1/2-1/2}) 10... O-O 11. Nd5 {Actually, this might be considered an
improvement over 10.Nd5, as after} Nd7 {It is like if Black had played 11...
0-0 in the game Tari-Ding Liren, allowing White to reinforce the outpost with}
12. Bc4 $1 {Although I think Black's position is good enough to reach equality
even in this case.} Rc8 13. Qe2 {[%cal Yf1d1] White follows his plan of
gradually cementing the Nd5.} (13. Bb3 {allows} Nc5 $1 {[%csl Ye4] that solves
Black's problems and leads to a simple endgame} 14. Nxf6+ (14. Re1 Nxb3 15.
cxb3 Rc6 $11) 14... Qxf6 15. Qxd6 Bxb3 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. axb3 Nxe4 $11 {
Rogic,D (2511)-Saric,I (2662) CRO-chT1A 26th 2017 (1.11) 1/2-1/2}) {As in
other variations analyzed, Black should play} 13... Nb6 $1 {[%csl Yc4,Yd5]
Before White is able to establish a firm control over d5.} 14. Nxb6 (14. Nxf6+
{is harmless} Qxf6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 {with the practical advantage that the knight
tends to be more useful for Black than the bishop would be in this position -
Dextre, E-King, D (2425) Geneve op 1985 0-1}) 14... Qxb6 15. Bb3 (15. Bxe6 fxe6
16. c3 {transposes to one line already seen} d5 $5) {In this position, the
most precise move for Black is} 15... Qc6 $1 {[%csl Yc2] Attacking c2, but
Black also keeps his eye on d5.} 16. c3 (16. Rfd1 Rfd8 17. c3 {transposes to
the game} (17. Qd3 $6 Bxb3 18. cxb3 Qc2 $1 $132)) 16... Rfd8 {[%cal Gd6d5]
Black manages to play d5 now.} 17. Rfd1 Bxb3 18. axb3 d5 $1 {and after} 19.
exd5 Rxd5 20. Rxd5 Qxd5 21. b4 Rd8 $11 {The position is very equal - Kurmann,O
(2459)-Georgiadis,N (2478) TCh-SUI 2017 2017 (8.2) 1/2-1/2} *

