{[%evp 0,48,24,28,45,40,73,61,61,44,44,29,43,21,41,50,50,24,17,-5,7,-3,15,9,31,
-3,52,14,43,29,26,21,21,20,10,1,11,-5,-5,-5,0,-20,-1,-40,-26,-29,-26,-29,-26,
-77,-36]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3
Be7 8. Bg5 {Like in the previous chapter, in this line White has the very
practical idea of playing Bg5xf6 and getting control over d5. The ideas are
very similar, but it is important to understand the differences of having the
knight on b3 now.} Be6 9. Bxf6 $1 {Again, White should exchange the knight
before Nbd7, in order to disturb Black's development a bit.} Bxf6 10. Qd3 {
[%cal Ge1c1] One of the differences is that White can go for 0-0-0 to get a
quick pressure against d6, and he can also increase the pressure on the centre
with g3-f4.} (10. Nd5 {gives Black extra options} Nd7 11. Qd3 Bg5 $1 {This way
Black prevents 0-0-0} (11... Be7 {would transpose to the main line}) 12. Rd1
O-O {it is interesting to note that the Nd5 is beautiful, but, at the same
time, it is also an obstacle for White in d-file} 13. c3 (13. Nc3 {Black is
well developed now and can even play} Rc8 $1 {sacrificing the pawn or
preparing to have a pleasant pressure on c-file with Rc6-Qc7-Rc8(d8)} 14. Qxd6
Be7 15. Qd3 Bb4 $1 16. O-O Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 {[%csl Gc3] and Black regains the
pawn with a better structure in the ending} 18. c4 Nb6 19. c5 Na4 $15) 13...
Kh8 14. O-O Rc8 15. Bf3 g6 {[%cal Yf7f5] Black has no problems and is already
playing for the initiative on the kingside.} 16. g3 f5 $36 {Kotsur,P (2548)
-Gelfand,B (2738) Wch Blitz 6th blitz 2012 (24) 0-1}) (10. O-O {is also
harmless} O-O 11. Qd3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Yc6b4,Yc6d4]} 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. Rfd1 Rc8 14.
c3 Ne7 $5 15. Nxe7+ Bxe7 16. Nd2 Qb6 $1 17. b3 Qc5 $15 {and Black had the
easier game - Meijers,V (2479) -Guliyev,N (2555) Lausanne op 2005 (4) 0-1})
10... Be7 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7] This is only the third move, but it is a very
promising one. Black prepares Nd7.} (10... Nc6 {is the most played}) 11. Nd5 (
11. O-O-O {is the second most played and seems a natural continuation of
White's plan} Nd7 12. Nd5 (12. g3 {[%cal Yf2f4] this is not dangerous because
Black manages to get active play on the queenside with} b5 $1 13. f4 {the
following game is quite instructive} O-O 14. f5 Bc4 15. Qf3 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Nb6
17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 {[%csl Gb3,Ye7] At first sight, the conclusion is that
White is very happy about the opening: he reached the desired knight vs bad
bishop. But things are not so simple as they may look...} Qc7 19. Kb1 Rfc8 $1 {
[%csl Gb1] White has problems to improve the knight in view of the bad
placement of his king, in the end, Black even achieved a real attack - Chirivi
Castiblanco,A (2037)-Rodriguez Rueda,P (2183) COL-ch U20 Girls 2013 (3) 0-1})
12... Bxd5 13. Qxd5 {In this position, my suggestion for Black is} b5 $5 $146 {
expanding on the queenside. I do not see how White could take advantage of
this move, so it seems like an improvement for Black, for example} (13... Qc7 {
is the main move}) 14. Kb1 (14. Bg4 Nf6 $1 15. Qc6+ Kf8 16. Bh3 g6 {[%cal
Yf8g7] and Black is fine}) (14. Na5 {[%cal Ga5c6] seems like a nice move, but
after} Rc8 15. Nc6 $2 {is just bad} Qc7 $19 {[%csl Rc2]}) 14... O-O {and it is
interesting because using a new move we've transposed into a position that was
already played twice, Black wants to play Qc7 with a nice position, so White
tried} 15. Qb7 $5 {but the queen had some problems after} Nf6 $1 16. f3 Re8 $1
{[%csl Rb7][%cal Ye7f8,Ye8e7] ;Duda,J (2579)-Yu,Y (2668) Tromsoe ol (Men) 41st
2014 (11.3) 0-1}) (11. Rd1 Nd7 12. Nd5 {transposes to the main line}) 11... Nd7
12. Rd1 {[%cal Yd1d8] The pressure on the d-file forces Black to give up his
better bishop.} (12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Rd1 Nf6 $1 {is ok for Black}) (12. O-O-O
Bxd5 13. Qxd5 b5 {transposes to an already seen position}) 12... Bxd5 13. Qxd5
Qc7 {This move is solid enough to give Black an equal game without problems.} (
{but} 13... b5 $5 {was played by Giri. It seems interesting as Black expands
on the queenside, as in the game Duda-Yu} 14. Bg4 $6 Nf6 $1 15. Qc6+ Kf8 16.
Bh3 g6 {even though White's play was aimed to disturb Black's development, he
is the one who is going to face some problems soon:} 17. O-O Kg7 18. Rfe1 Ra7
$1 {[%cal Ya7c7]} 19. Qc3 Qb6 20. Qe3 Qxe3 21. Rxe3 a5 22. a3 Rb8 $15 {and
Black had an initiative on the queenside - Nisipeanu, L (2672)-Giri, A (2782)
46th GM 2018 2018 (4.1) 0-1}) 14. c3 ({Carlsen once tried} 14. Nd2 O-O 15. O-O
b5 $1 16. c3 {but this transposes to the main line}) 14... O-O 15. O-O b5 $1 {
The positional question here is if White will be able to maneuver the knight
to d5. Of course, it is not an easy task, parting from b3, but Black should be
aware of this plan and take care to not end in a slightly inferior and passive
position.} 16. Nd2 {Playing with patience.} (16. Na1 $5 {[%cal Ga1c2,Gc2e3]
seems more direct, but it will cost at least 2 moves for White to bring this
knight back to the game} Rad8 $1 {[%cal Yd7f6,Yd6d5]} 17. Bf3 Nb6 18. Qb3 {
Black has a nice idea now to stop worrying about the d5-square:} Kh8 $1 19. Nc2
d5 $1 {this break comes just in time, and it is basically the refutation of 16.
Na1} 20. Ne3 (20. exd5 f5 $1 {gives Black a nice compensation, for example} 21.
Nb4 Bxb4 22. Qxb4 Rf6 $44 {[%cal Ge5e4,Yf6d6,Yf6h6]}) 20... dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bc5
22. Nd5 Nxd5 23. Bxd5 f5 {and Black was at least ok in Almasi, Z (2702)
-Yakubboev,N (2521) 43rd Olympiad 2018 2018 (3.24) 1/2-1/2}) 16... g6 {Black
also does not need to rush, but it is important to pay attention to White's
ideas, which are sometimes very subtle. The following game is very instructive
on this subject.} (16... Nb6 17. Qb3 Rac8 18. Rfe1 Bg5 19. Nf3 Be7 20. Nd2 Bg5
$11 {Jakovenko,D (2722)-Karjakin, S (2785) RUS-ch 65th Moscow 2012 (6) 1/2-1/2}
) 17. a3 $5 {[%cal Gc3c4]} (17. c4 b4 $1 {[%cal Yd7c5]}) 17... Rab8 $1 {
White was threatening c4 which would have given him a pleasant endgame.} ({
For example} 17... Rfe8 $2 18. c4 $1 Nb6 19. Qd3 bxc4 20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Qxc4
Qxc4 22. Bxc4 $14 {[%csl Gc4] such endgames are always pleasant for White
because of the better minor piece}) 18. Rfe1 (18. c4 b4 $15) 18... Rfd8 19. Qa2
$5 (19. Nf1 {[%cal Yf1e3]} Nf6 $1 {White is always one tempo down to fulfil
his dreams} 20. Qd3 d5 $36) 19... Nc5 20. Bf1 Bg5 $1 {Black can improve his
pieces and at the same time avoid the landing of the knight on d5.} 21. Nb3 (
21. Nf3 Be7 {and the White's knight remains far from its ideal square.}) 21...
Qc6 $5 {[%csl Ye4]} 22. Na5 (22. Nxc5 dxc5 23. Rd5 {is harmless for Black due
to} c4 $1) (22. f3 $2 d5 $1 $36) 22... Qc7 23. Nb3 Qc6 24. Rd5 Nd7 $1 {[%cal
Yd7b6,Yd7f6,Gd6d5] And Black is ok, eventually, he even managed to get some
initiative. Giri's games in the Najdorf are also very instructive, especially
in such structures, as he knows how to deal with the d5-square and how to play
for a win with Black in these positions very well - Carlsen, M (2834) -Giri, A 
(2784) Qatar Masters op 2015 (7) 1/2-1/2} *

