{[%evp 0,46,16,28,40,40,79,57,57,44,44,18,39,50,50,46,46,46,46,42,32,28,45,13,
-8,1,-14,-55,-44,-52,10,12,-3,-25,-8,-29,21,-13,7,7,7,-50,-3,-24,-24,-24,-13,
-20,-13] In this chapter, we will analyze an agressive approach when White
tries to play energically on the kingside. As Black has a solid set-up, he
should be ok, but it is important to know some ideas because the game can
become sharp.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7.
Nb3 Be7 {[%csl Yc8] As mentioned in chapter 2, it is always advisable to keep
the light-squared bishop flexible.} (7... Be6 8. f4 $5 {[%cal Yf4f5] promises
the initiative for White}) 8. O-O {As we will see some aggressive ideas in
this chapter, it is interesting to study other mover orders and tricky ideas,
too.} ({For example, if} 8. Be3 $5 {Black should play} Be6 $1 (8... O-O $6 {
is a bit risky because White can take advantage of the fact that his king has
not been committed to the kingside yet and launch an attack with} 9. g4 $1 Be6
10. g5 Nfd7 11. h4 $40 {[%cal Yd1d2,Ye1c1,Gf2f4] and White had a promising
attack in Carlsen,M (2814) -Nakamura,H (2751) Tata Steel-A 73rd 2011 (8) 1-0})
{now White should play} 9. O-O (9. g4 {does not work now in view of} d5 $1 {
which gives Black a nice position after} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 $36) 9...
O-O {transposing to the text. An interesting and practical way to avoid
falling for such tricky mover orders is to use the opponent's last move as a
"signal" for one's own moves: If White has played Be2, then Be7; if White has
played Be3, then Be6; if White has played a4, then Nc6. Of course, you should
take the particular position into account, but it is a method that works
reasonably well :)}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 (9. f4 $6 {is too rushed, but it is
important to understand the reason behind it: Whenever White plays this move,
the e4-pawn becomes a weakness, and now Black can play} b5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal
Yc8b7] with good pressure against e4} 10. Bf3 Nbd7 11. Kh1 Bb7 {and Black has
an active development - Silva Sanchez,C (2388) -Kovalyov,A (2557) Dos Hermanas
Internet qual-D 10th blitz 2009 (3) 0-1}) ({but} 9. Kh1 {is a useful,
preparatory move. White can also wait and see if Black develops the bishop to
e6, but he can keep things undefined by means of} Nc6 $5 (9... b5 $6 {is risky
due to} 10. a4 $1 Bb7 11. Nd5 $1 $36) (9... b6 {seems most solid and playable.
It makes sense for White now to restrict the bishop on the long diagonal.} 10.
Be3 Bb7 11. f3 b5 $5 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nd7 $13) 10. f4 (10. Be3
Be6 11. Qd2 d5 $5 {Black is ready to play d5 and equalize} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13.
Nxd5 Bxd5 $11) {Again} 10... b5 $1 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gc8b7] is the right move}
11. Bf3 (11. Be3 {was played by Carlsen} Bb7 12. a4 exf4 13. Rxf4 Ne5 $1 {
[%csl Ye4][%cal Ge5g6] threatening ideas against e4} 14. Qd4 Nc6 15. Qd2 Ne5 $1
16. Qd4 Nc6 17. Qd2 Ne5 $11 {instead of accepting the repetition, Magnus tried
to be ambitious with} 18. axb5 axb5 19. Re1 $6 {but this brought him some
problems after} Ng6 20. Rff1 b4 21. Nd5 Nxe4 $1 22. Nxe7+ Qxe7 23. Qxb4 Nh4 $1
{[%cal Rh4g2,Rb7h1] and Black suddenly had a dangerous initiative - Carlsen,M 
(2814)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2733) Tata Steel-A 73rd 2011 (10) 0-1}) (11. a4 $5 {
is a normal reaction to b7-b5, then} Bb7 {seems to be a safe move and was
played 4 times, 3 of them by Sutovsky (!). Black is better prepared to play
b5-b4 or to exert pressure on e4 now, and if} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14.
Bxb5 Na7 $1 {[%csl Yb5,Ye4] Black restores the material equality} 15. Bd3 Nxe4
16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Qxe4 $11 {Efimenko,Z (2590)-Sutovsky,E (2651) Moscow
Aeroflot op-A 2003 (8) 1/2-1/2}) {Now} 11... Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] seems to be a
good way to reach equality.} (11... Bb7 {[%cal Ga8c8] is also playable}) 12.
Nxa5 Qxa5 13. fxe5 (13. Qe1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Yb5b4]} 14. a3 Be6 15.
f5 Bc4 16. Be2 d5 $1 {gave Black the initiative in Smirin,I (2649) -Grischuk,A
(2719) EU-Cup 24th Kallithea 2008 (6) 0-1}) 13... dxe5 14. Bg5 {[%csl Yd5]
White plays to win the d5 outpost, but he is not able to accomplish his plan}
Bb7 ({Black also had a nice position after} 14... Rd8 15. Qe1 Bb7 16. Qg3 b4 $1
17. Nd1 Qc7 18. Nf2 Ne8 $1 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Be2 Nf6 21. Bd3 Nh5 $15 {[%cal
Yh5f4] ;Quparadze,G (2467)-Sutovsky,E (2700) Baku op-A 2011 (2) 0-1}) 15. Qe1
$5 {[%cal Gc3d5] again with the threat of Nd5} (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 {seems
harmless for Black} Rad8 $1 17. Nxf6+ $6 gxf6 18. Qe2 Qd2 $1 {and Black won't
have problems on the kingside.}) 15... Qc7 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 16. a3 Ne8 $1 {
this exchange is a typical positional operation, as Black gets rid of his bad
bishop and stays with the better pawn structure for the endgames} 17. Bxe7 (17.
Bd2 $142) 17... Qxe7 18. a4 Nd6 19. a5 $2 Rac8 $15 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yc8c2,
Yc8c4] ;Dervishi,E (2552)-Ibrahimov,R (2518) World Blitz 2017 blitz 2017 (15.
51) 0-1}) 9... Be6 {Now, as Black defined the light-squared bishop's position,
White plays} 10. f4 $6 {Honestly, I do not think this is a good move, as Black
is very solid and has some dynamic ideas now due to the weakening of White's
kingside. But it is important to know how to play precisely as Black too.} ({
another way to play the f4-idea is} 10. a4 Nc6 $5 {[%csl Gb4]} 11. f4 $6 {
although it seems even less effective here as Black has one more piece
developed.} d5 $1 {This counterblow in the center was played only 3 times, but
seems a very strong response to 11.f4} 12. exd5 (12. f5 d4 $1 13. fxe6 fxe6 14.
Bc4 dxe3 $1 15. Bxe6+ Kh8 {[%cal Gc6d4] and Black's position seems easier, for
example} 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. Nd5 Rd6 $1 18. Nxe7 Nxe7 19. Bc4 Rc8 20. Bd3 Nc6
$36 {[%cal Yc6b4]}) 12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 {usually such
positions offer an easier game for Black due to the many open lines in the
center and the fact that White's king is a bit exposed, which may give some
practical problems for White} 15. Qd2 (15. Qd4 $2 Bf6 $1 $17) 15... Nc4 $1 16.
Bxc4 Bxc4 17. Rfd1 Qxd2 18. Rxd2 Rfc8 $15 {[%csl Gc4,Ge7] the endgame is more
pleasant for Black.}) 10... exf4 $1 11. Bxf4 {[%csl Yd5,Ge5] Another point is
that White has lost one tempo with his bishop going to e3 and then f4. This
structure is very important to understand, as it can arise in many Najdorf
variations. Both sides have new ideas now: White has the open f-file and
chances of bringing his pieces to the kingside, with Nd4-f5 for example,
attacking different parts of the board. In return, Black can also use the same
open lines to explore the now exposed opponent's king, and like d5, e5 is a
stable central post to put either a bishop or a knight. The d5-square remains
an important point, but due to the newly-opened lines, the game tends to be
sharper, with chances for both sides.} (11. Rxf4 {gives some different ideas
for White, but it does not seem enough to get an advantage} Nc6 12. Nd5 $5 {
the only way of justifying the capture with the rook on f4} (12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4
Nd7 $1 {[%cal Yd7e5,Ge7g5] is ok for Black}) (12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rd1 Ne5 {It is
difficult for White to even create threats as Black is very solid in the
center.} 14. Nd4 b5 15. a3 g6 $1 {[%csl Gf5] the f5-square is very important
because an eventual capture Nxe6 would only fix Black's structure.} 16. Rdf1
Bc4 $1 {and Black is fine again, after} 17. Kh1 $2 {he even took the
initiative with} d5 $1 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 {Kantane,A (2259)-Xiong,
J (2667) PRO League Stage rapid 2017 (5) 0-1}) 12... Bxd5 $1 13. exd5 Ne5 {
a new transformation of the pawn structure occurred and we need to pay
attention again: from my practical experience, Black's game will be easier
from here if he succeeds in finding nice squares for the knights (considering
that one of them is already excellently placed). Trading off the dark-squared
bishops is also an improvement, as the light-squared bishop is White's bad one.
You will find a more detailed explanation of this structure in the
structure database.} 14. Rb4 $5 ({for example} 14. c4 Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5,
Ge7g5]} 15. Rf1 Rc8 16. Rc1 Bg5 $1 {is an instructive example of how Black can
improve his position strategically.} 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Nd4 g6 19. Rc3 Nc5 20.
Rg3 Qd8 21. b3 Re8 $15 {Kula,R (2341) -Olszewski,M (2526) Police Gniota
Memorial 27th 2012 (4) 0-1}) 14... Qc7 15. a4 {intending to cramp Black's
queenside. An easy way to organize the pieces now is} Nfd7 16. a5 Bf6 {the
Black pieces cooperate very well to defend many important squares} 17. Qd2 Rfe8
18. Rf1 Ng6 $5 19. c3 Re5 $1 {[%cal Ya8e8]} 20. Rc4 Qd8 21. Bg4 Qe8 $1 {
and Black is already playing for an advantage} 22. Bf2 (22. Rc7 Rxe3 $1 23.
Bxd7 Qd8 24. Rxb7 Re7 25. Bc6 Rxb7 26. Bxb7 Rb8 $19 {[%csl Rb3,Rb7]}) 22... Bg5
$1 23. Qd1 Nf6 $1 24. Bf3 Be3 $1 {forcing the desired exchange of the
dark-squared bishops, which leaves Black with good practical chances in the
ensuing endgames - Li, R (2446)-Troff, K (2517) Saint Louis SPICE Cup op 9th
2015 (3) 0-1}) 11... Nc6 12. Kh1 {This move is advisable prophylaxis after the
advance of the f-pawn.} (12. Qe1 {[%cal Ye1g3,Ya1d1] White wants to transfer
the queen to the kingside and at the same time increase the pressure on d6.
There's a nice move now that prevents both ideas:} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6,Ye7g5,
Ye7f6] the knight seems modest on e8, but it allows Black to achieve the best
placement possible to his pieces:} 13. Rd1 (13. Nd5 Bg5 $1 14. Bg3 Nf6 $1 {
Black's position can be compared to a spring, the pieces first went back, but
now they go ahead!} 15. Nc3 Qe7 16. Rd1 Rad8 {[%cal Yd6d5] and Black achieved
the d5-advance, solving his problems - Arnason, J (2460) -Szekely, P (2435)
Keres Memorial-04 1983 (12) 1/2-1/2}) 13... Bh4 $1 {diverting the queen from
her destination} 14. Qd2 Bf6 $1 {[%csl Ye5,Ge6,Ge8,Gf6] Despite their cramped
appearance, Black's pieces are well placed with the bishop pair creating
pressure on the queenside and the important e5-square being firmly under
control.} 15. Nd5 $5 {looking to complicate matters, although Black is
sufficiently solid} (15. Bxd6 Nxd6 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Rfe8 {seems to offer
great compensation to Black in form of active play, for example,} 18. Bf3 Be5
19. Rd2 Rac8 20. Rfd1 Bxc3 $1 21. bxc3 Ne5 $15 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gc8c3]}) 15...
Bxb2 16. c3 (16. Bg5 $5 f6 17. Be3 Be5 18. c3 $13 {White has some compensation,
but probably not enough}) 16... Ba3 17. Bg5 f6 18. Be3 Bxd5 $5 19. exd5 Ne5 20.
Kh1 Rc8 21. Nd4 Qa5 $1 {White has some compensation because of the e6-square,
but he also has some weaknesses on the queenside to take care of - Mainka,R 
(2476)-Pigusov,E (2609) MK Cafe Cup-A 1999 (6) 0-1}) (12. Qd2 {is also
harmless for Black} b5 $1 13. Bf3 Ne5 $132 {[%cal Ye5f3,Ye5c4] ;Lianes Garcia,
M (2144) -Grigoryan,K (2602) Roquetas de Mar op 27th 2016 (1) 0-1}) {The
easiest way for Black now is} 12... d5 $1 (12... Rc8 $5 {is the main move and
looks interesting if Black wants to keep more pieces on the board. The most
natural continuation for White now is} 13. Qe1 {and then} Ne8 $1 {is possible,
with similar ideas to those analyzed in the previous note}) 13. e5 $5 {The
only attempt if White intends to keep some unbalance.} (13. exd5 {leads to
many simplifications, and an equal endgame} Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 15. Bf3 Qxd1
16. Raxd1 Rad8 17. c3 Rfe8 $11 {my experience in such endgames has taught me
that Black even has some small practical chances to play for a win here, as
his pieces can put White's queenside under pressure more easily - Lewicki,M 
(2404)-Krzyzanowski,M (2457) XXXVI Zamenhofa Mem 2017 (6.10) 0-1}) 13... Ne4 $1
{Black should keep playing energically.} (13... Nd7 14. Nxd5 Ndxe5 15. c4 {
[%csl Gd5] gives White some chances because of the well placed Nd5}) 14. Bd3 (
14. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 15. Nd2 {is harmless as after} Bg5 $1 {the position is equal}
16. Nxe4 Bxf4 $11 {[%csl Ye5] ;Karpov,A-Najdorf,M Christmas Congress 1971/
72-47 Premier 1971 (13) 1/2-1/2}) {Now, I think the new attempt} 14... Nc5 $5
$146 {is a possibility to avoid exchanges which would lead to an equal
position. The idea is to create some problems for White in the defense of e5.}
(14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 g6 {is a safe option}) 15. Nxc5 (15. Be2 Nxb3 16. axb3 Qd7
17. Bf3 Rad8 {[%cal Yf8e8] is ok for Black}) 15... Bxc5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8e8,
Gd8c7,Gc5f8,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] White has not a clear plan, but Black's idea is very
clear and easy: slowly increase the pressure on e5, with moves like Re8, Qc7
and eventually Bf8-g6-Bg7.} 16. Qf3 (16. Qe1 {is another way to develop the
queen that seems even more natural} Bd4 $1 17. Qg3 Qc7 18. Rae1 Rfe8 19. Qh4 {
transposing to the text}) 16... Bd4 $1 {[%csl Re5]} 17. Rae1 Re8 (17... Qc7 $2
18. Nxd5 $16) 18. Qg3 ({White can try} 18. Nd1 {[%cal Yc2c3] but Black has} Nb4
$1 19. c3 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Bb6 21. Qg3 Bc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5f8,Yd5d4]} 22. Bh6 Bf8 23.
Be3 b5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 18... Qc7 19. Qh4 $1 {It seems to be a good
strategy to provoke weaknesses in Black's camp.} g6 20. a3 $1 {Preventing
Nb4-ideas.} Rac8 21. Qg3 Na5 $5 {[%cal Ya5c4,Gc8c1] The position is complex,
but Black has some unpleasant ideas such as Nc4 or even Bxc3.} 22. Bh6 $1 (22.
Nd1 {[%cal Yc2c3,Gd1e3] is also interesting, intending to drive back the
bishop from d4 and then to recycle the knight to the kingside.} Nc4 23. c3 Bb6
24. Bxc4 $5 Qxc4 $1 25. Ne3 Qb5 $1 {and even here Black is still solid, for
example} 26. Ng4 Bxg4 27. Qxg4 Re6 $1 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Yd5d4] stopping e5-e6}
28. Bh6 $1 Qe8 $1 $11 (28... Qxb2 $4 29. Rb1 $18 {[%csl Rb6]})) 22... Nc6 {
[%csl Ye5]} (22... Bxc3 $2 {[%csl Rg8] seems to be simply a bad idea from a
practical point of view.}) 23. Bf4 Na5 $11 {Repeating moves is probably the
safer option for both sides.} *

