this position it is difficult to find any advantage in White's set-up} 14. Rfd1
Rfc8 15. Rac1 g6 {[%cal Ye7f8,Yf8g7] the dark-squared bishop will have better
prospects from g7, and the kingside pawns can advance in the future.} 16. h3 {
Hou, Y (2676) -Nepomniachtchi, I (2720) Dortmund SuperGM 43rd 2015 (7) 1/2-1/2}
Nc5 17. Nxc5 Qxc5 18. c4 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Yf7f5] one important point of the
moves a5/a4 here is that White has difficulties to expand on the queenside,
while Black's counterplay on the other wing is normal.}) 9... Be6 10. Nd5 $5 {
This move ensures a transformation in the pawn structure.} Nbd7 $1 {Now Black
threatens to take on e4, thus forcing the White queen to be a bit exposed.} (
10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Nbd7 12. c4 {is similar to the text, but the fact that the
White queen remains on d1 gives White some extra options.}) (10... Nxe4 $6 11.
Bb6 {[%cal Yd5c7] and Black should sacrifice an exchange, but this idea did
not gain many followers.}) (10... Nxd5 $6 {as we will see, it is better for
Black to keep the knights in this structure.} 11. exd5 Bf5 12. Qd2 a5 (12...
Nd7 13. Na5 $1 Qc7 14. c4 {[%cal Yb2b4]}) 13. f4 $1 {and White took over the
initiative.} exf4 (13... a4 14. fxe5 axb3 15. Rxf5 Rxa2 16. Raf1 $1 $36 {
[%cal Ge5e6]}) 14. Rxf4 Bg6 15. Ra4 $1 b6 16. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ye2b5] ;
Svidler,P (2650)-Gelfand,B (2665) Tilburg Fontys 1996 (10) 1/2-1/2}) 11. Qd3 (
11. Nxe7+ {helps Black} Qxe7 {[%cal Gd6d5] from now, White tries to prevent
the advance d6-d5, but in vain} 12. Bf3 Rfd8 13. Qd2 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Nf8 15. Bg5
h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Rac1 Ng6 18. Qe3 Nh4 $1 19. Nd2 d5 20. exd5 Bxd5 $15 {
Evans,L-Rossolimo,N USA-ch New York,NY 1965 (1) 0-1}) 11... Bxd5 $1 {It is
better to take on d5 without giving White the chance of playing c4-cxd5.} 12.
exd5 {[%csl Gd5] This is another typical structure that should be known to
Najdorf players. In the previous chapters, I have said that it is usually good
for Black when White ends up with a pawn on d5, as it cuts the pressure on the
d-file and the d6 pawn. But in this case, White has more space as well as the
bishop pair, and he also expects to use the newly-created majority on the
queenside to create a passed pawn, or to put Black under pressure.} Rc8 {
Black's ideas are typically rather connected to using his pawns on the
kingside striving for active counterplay. But I like this move first, keeping
an eye on the opponent's queenside.} 13. c4 Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 14. Qd2 {
[%cal Gb3a5,Gb2b4] The ideal continuation for White would be Na5 and b4, with
the desired pressure on Black's camp.} (14. Bg4 {was played against me, but
Black has a nice idea now:} e4 $1 {which forces many simplifications or simply
gives mobility to Black's kingside} 15. Qxe4 (15. Qe2 f5 16. Bh3 {[%cal Yb3d4,
Yd4e6] White has the idea of Nd4-e6 now} g6 $1 17. Nd4 Ng7 18. Bh6 {Lobanov,S 
(2457)-Shevchenko,K (2531) 2nd European Youth GP 2017 (8.2) 0-1} Bf6 19. Bxg7
Bxg7 20. Ne6 Qh4 21. Nxf8 Rxf8 $44 {[%csl Gg7,Gh3][%cal Yg6g5,Yg5g4,Gd7c5,
Gd7e5] Black has clear compensation for the exchange here, his pieces can be
very active playing on the dark squares and the Bh3 is out of play.}) 15...
Nef6 $1 16. Qd4 Nxg4 17. Qxg4 Ne5 {[%csl Yc4] the point of Black's 14th move}
18. Qe2 Nxc4 19. Bd4 Re8 $11 {and after the exchanges Black is ok - Duran Vega,
S (2287)-Quintiliano, R (2441) Continental das Américas - El Salvador (6.12)
0-1}) 14... b6 $5 {A double-edged move, played by Grischuk and Mamedyarov.
Black intends to restrict the Nb3, but the c6-square can cause some concerns.}
(14... f5 {is also playable} 15. f4 g6 16. Na5 exf4 17. Bxf4 Nef6 $1 {[%cal
Yf6e4] gave Black good counterplay in Hovhannisyan, R (2592)-Areshchenko, A 
(2701) Lake Sevan Martuni 2014 (7.2) 0-1}) 15. Rac1 $1 a5 16. Na1 $1 {A
creative way to improve the knight.} f5 ({Grischuk tried an original plan} 
16... g6 {[%csl Ye8,Yf5] avoiding f7-f5 in order to keep that square available
