{In this chapter, we will deal with the so-called quiet lines. It means those
variations in which White does not play so concretely as in the last two
chapters. Instead, he is going for slow play, looking for subtle maneuvers and
small improvements in order to play with a small advantage and an easier
position. Black should be aware of these plans and move orders to avoid ending
in an unpleasant position that may prove difficult to play in practice.} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O
9. Be3 (9. Re1 $5 {is a less played but interesting option} Be6 10. Bf3 {
[%csl Yd5] White's development is directed to control the center} Nbd7 11. a4
$1 {and then the queenside. The ideas behind 9.Re1 are not so obvious, but
they become clear if Black plays carelessly.} Qb8 $1 {the best plan to
neutralize White's regroupment} (11... Qc7 12. a5 $1 Rfc8 {is also a natural
development for Black, but White obtained a long-term advantage} 13. Be3 b5 $5
14. axb6 Nxb6 {[%cal Yb6c4]} 15. Na5 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Nc4 16. Nxc4 Qxc4 17.
Na4 $1 {[%csl Gb6]} Nd7 $8 18. Re2 Rab8 19. b3 Qb4 20. Bc1 $1 Qb7 21. Bb2 h6
22. h3 Rc7 23. Re3 $1 {the last moves of White are very instructive} Rbc8 24.
c4 $14 {[%csl Ga6,Gd6] and White had exactly the small advantage that he aims
for in such structures, with an easier game and good practical chances in the
arising endgames - Jakovenko, D (2718)-Donchenko, A (2563) EU-ch 18th Minsk 2017
(8) 1-0}) 12. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yb3d2,Yd2f1,Yf1e3] the main idea in this
line is the quick improvement of the Nb3, looking to increase the control over
d5.} (12. a5 {is not effective now because Black plays} Rc8 13. Be3 Bd8 14. Qd2
b5 $1 15. axb6 Bxb3 16. cxb3 Bxb6 $11 {and he has no problems - Lagno,K (2530)
-Shankland, S (2674) Gibraltar Masters 15th 2017 (10) 1/2-1/2}) {Black has his
own strong maneuver now:} 12... Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8a5] This operation is very
similar to White's one on the other side with Bg5xf6: the objective is to pin
the Nc3 and get rid of the bad bishop, at the same time decreasing White's
control over d5. A remarkable idea!} 13. Nf1 Ba5 $1 14. Bd2 Qc7 {this
regroupment of Black's pieces should be remembered as it represents the
perfect antidote to this line} 15. Ne3 {the most forcing way for Black now is}
Bxc3 $1 ({despite the fact that} 15... Rac8 {was played in two MVL games}) 16.
Bxc3 Nc5 {[%csl Ye4] due to the pressure on e4, White tried some complications
with} 17. Nf5 $5 {Ruan,L (2492) -Ju,W (2528) Ankara FIDE GP (Women) 2012 (9) 1/
2-1/2} (17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bd7 $1 19. a5 Na4 $1 {is also easier for Black}
20. Qd2 Nxc3 21. bxc3 {Rodriguez Dominguez,M (2051)-Forgas Moreno,Y (2228)
CUB-ch (Women) 2016 (15) 1-0} Bb5 $17 {[%cal Ya8c8,Gf7f5]}) 17... Nfxe4 $5 {
probably would give Black an easier game} 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Nxg7 (19. Nh6+ $2
gxh6 20. Rxe4 f6 $15) 19... Nxc3 $1 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. bxc3 Rf4 $1 {[%cal Ya8f8]
with chances for both sides, although Black's play seems easier, as White has
some weaknesses on the queenside, and his king is not as exposed as it may
look.}) (9. a4 {is another normal and good move in such positions, keeping the
counterplay on the queenside under control.} Be6 {[%cal Yd6d5]} (9... Nc6 $5 {
[%cal Yc6b4] is also playable}) 10. Bf3 Nbd7 11. a5 {It is likely that White
is going to transpose to 9.Re1 as he can play this move at any moment. I found
the following game very instructive} Rc8 12. Re1 {For example, in this
position the Qb8-Bd8-Ba5 idea is not available, but Black has other ways to
play and get a good position.} Qc7 13. Be3 Rfd8 14. Nd2 {After establishing a
firm grip in the center and on the queenside, White starts to improve the
knight.} h6 $5 {preparing an interesting idea} 15. Nf1 Nh7 $1 16. Ng3 Bg5 $1 {
a nice way to deal with the lack of space, forcing exchanges, and at the same
time getting rid of the bad bishop} 17. Nf5 Bxe3 18. Nxe3 Nhf6 19. Qd2 Nc5 $1
20. Ncd5 (20. Red1 Qc6 {[%csl Ye4] forces} 21. Ncd5 {anyway}) 20... Bxd5 21.
exd5 Ncd7 22. c4 g6 {Svidler,P (2727)-Maslak,K (2544) RUS-ch Superfinal 61st
2008 (5) 1/2-1/2 and the position is complex, White aims to advance his
queenside, but Black is solid enough there to stop the pawns, and his pawns
advancing in the center and on the kingside may generate strong counterplay -})
9... Be6 10. Qd2 (10. a4 {Black can now play} Nc6 $5 {[%csl Gb4]} 11. Bf3 Na5
12. Nxa5 Qxa5 13. Qd2 Rfc8 $1 {is harmless for Black,for example} 14. Rfd1 (14.
Nd5 $6 Qxd2 15. Nxe7+ Kf8 16. Bxd2 Rxc2 $1 17. Bc3 Kxe7 18. Bd1 {[%csl Gc2]}
Rxc3 $1 19. bxc3 Nxe4 $17) 14... Kf8 $1 {preventing Nd5, and Black is fine} 15.
Qc1 {[%cal Yd1d3,Yc1d2]} Rc4 $1 16. Rd3 Rac8 {and Black is fine - Kamsky,G 
(2705)-Gelfand,B (2733) Wch Candidates final 2007 (2.1) 1/2-1/2}) 10... Nbd7
11. a4 (11. f4 {does not pose problems for Black.} Qc7 12. f5 Bc4 13. Bxc4 (13.
g4 $6 {seems aggressive, but the typical response} d5 $1 {[%cal Ge7b4] is
enough to give Black the initiative, for example} 14. g5 $1 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe2
16. Qxe2 dxe4 17. Qg4 Bc5 $1 18. Nxc5 Nxc5 19. f6 g6 $13 {[%cal Yc5e6]}) 13...
Qxc4 14. Qd3 Rfc8 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gc8c1] and Black is at least ok, although
he has good reasons to want more}) 11... Rc8 12. a5 {[%csl Ga5] This position
is quite typical and it is often played by technical players who want to use
their space advantage to slowly improve the position and cramp Black. As
mentioned in some notes, Black should be patient and place his pieces
correctly, also looking for some typical ideas that may improve his position.}
Re8 13. Rfd1 (13. Bf3 {was played in a recent game} h6 14. Nc1 {[%csl Yd5]
[%cal Gc1d3,Gd3b4]} Nh7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5] the idea which we have already seen
in some positions} 15. g3 Bg5 $1 16. Nd3 (16. Qxd6 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Ng5 18. Bg2
Nf6 $1 {gives Black nice compensation} 19. Qxd8 Rexd8 20. h4 Nh3+ 21. Kh2 Rd2
$1 $36 {[%cal Yf6g4]}) 16... Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6d4] the way how Black
improves his pieces is quite instructive, the knight aims to go to d4 now.} 17.
Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Qxg5 hxg5 $1 19. Rfd1 Nc6 20. Ne2 g4 21. Bg2 Ng5 $15 {and almost
naturally Black achieved a clear advantage in Zherebukh, Y (2633)-Xiong,J 
(2640) St Louis Spring A 2018 (1.4) 0-1}) 13... h6 14. f3 {This is solid
although both sides will find it difficult to make real progress.} (14. Nc1 {
White's idea is Nd3-b4 or Na2-b4 reaching d5} Qc7 15. Bf3 (15. Nd3 d5 $1 16.
exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Nxe5 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Yc2,Ye5]} 19. Ng4 $5 Qxc2 20.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Qxd5 Qxe2 $11) {now} 15... b5 $1 {comes just in time to give
Black an active play. This move seems especially effective when White has the
knight on c1, as the Nc4 threat becomes quite annoying.} 16. axb6 (16. Nd3 {
can be met by} d5 $1 $146 17. exd5 Bf5 {[%cal Ge5e4,Yb5b4] Black plays with
nice compensation for the pawn, for example} 18. Ne1 Bd6 19. g3 Qb7 $44 {
[%cal Gd7c5,Ye8d8,Ye5e4,Yd6b4] with a lot of threats, and White's pieces are
badly placed too}) 16... Nxb6 {[%cal Yb6c4]} 17. Be2 Nc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Qe1
Qb7 $1 20. b3 Be6 21. f3 d5 $17 {Black is already better - Nevostrujev,V (2495)
-Efimenko,Z (2594) Chigorin Memorial 12th 2004 (8) 0-1}) 14... Qc7 15. Nc1 Bf8
16. Bf1 (16. Nd3 {is not possible again due} d5 $1 {that gives Black a free
game}) 16... Red8 17. Qe1 {Both sides have developed their pieces well, but no
useful ideas are apparent. The simplest is} Qc6 {[%cal Gd6d5] That basically
forces the repetition.} 18. Qd2 Qc7 19. Qe1 Qc6 20. Qd2 Qc7 $11 {Nakamura,H 
(2772) -Korobov,A (2720) FIDE World Cup 2013 (4.1) 1/2-1/2} *

