1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 $5 {
Again, the same structure in a different move order. At this point, we are
already used with the ideas for both sides, but once more it is important to
pay attention to some differences in the placement of the pieces. Compared to 6.Be2,
White has the possibility of playing Bc4 directly which seems more natural to
control d5. But the also typical Bg5 idea will cost two tempos now. Getting
everything is always difficult in chess :)} (7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 {leads to the
typical and double-edged positions of the English Attack, that will be
examined in the next database}) 7... Be7 (7... Be6 $6 {seems bad due to} 8. Ng5
) (7... Qc7 {prevents Bc4, but the queen may be misplaced on c7 after} 8. a4 $1
{[%csl Gb6][%cal Ya4a5] although this is played by the young American GM Xiong,
who is a specialist in the Najdorf. A recent game showed that White is faster
to accomplish his plans.} h6 9. a5 Be6 10. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. c4 Nd7
13. Be2 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. b4 Bh7 16. Rc1 Rac8 17. Qb3 Kh8 (17... f5 18. c5 $1
{[%cal Yb3g8]}) 18. Nd2 f5 19. f4 $1 {White stopped the counterplay on the
kingside while keeping nice prospects on the other side - Karthikeyan, M (2609)
-Fedoseev, V (2707) 25th Abu Dhabi Masters 2018 (7.6) 1-0}) 8. Bc4 (8. a4 {
although this move was played by a few GMs, I think it is unnecessary, as the
counterplay on the queenside is not really dangerous and White commits some
squares in queenside.} O-O 9. Bc4 (9. a5 Be6 10. Be2 h6 $1 {preventing Ng5} 11.
O-O Nbd7 {Black developed his pieces in a normal way, while White didn't
achieve anything with the a4-a5 idea} 12. Nd2 {[%cal Ye2c4]} Rc8 $1 13. f3 Qc7
14. Rf2 $6 {[%cal Yd2f1]} d5 $1 {Black is already better - Meijers,V (2483)
-Zhang,Z (2607) Ubeda op 6th 2001 (5) 0-1}) 9... Nc6 {[%csl Gb4] as we saw in
many examples, this way of developing the knight is attractive due to the
weakness created on b4.} 10. O-O Be6 11. Qe2 (11. Nd2 d5 $1 12. exd5 Nxd5 13.
Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Qe2 Qd7 15. Rfd1 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Rac8 $11 {Bologan,V (2700)
-Areshchenko,A (2595) RUS-chT Sochi 2005 (1) 1/2-1/2}) 11... Rc8 12. Nd5 $5
Bxd5 13. exd5 {Sarana,A (2510) -Potkin,V (2576) RUS-ch Higher League 70th 2017
(7) 1/2-1/2} (13. Bxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb4 $1 15. c4 $8 a5 $1 {Black can use his
pawns in kingside without care about counterplay on the other side - Nomin
Erdene, D (2490)-Bruzon Batista,L (2679) Dubai op 18th 2016 (3) 1/2-1/2}) {
Black could play now} 13... Nb4 14. Rfd1 Nxc2 $1 {as after} 15. Qxc2 b5 16.
axb5 axb5 17. b3 bxc4 18. bxc4 Ng4 {his position is at least ok}) 8... O-O 9.
O-O Be6 $1 {It is important for Black start to thinking about d5 in this line,
as compared to the previous chapters, White is better developed to achieve a
positional advantage.} 10. Bb3 (10. Bxe6 {is harmless, despite a memorable
Ivanchuk win with this line} fxe6 11. Na4 $5 Ng4 $1 12. Qd3 Nxe3 13. Qxe3 b5
14. Nb6 Ra7 15. Nd5 $1 Rb7 16. Qd2 $1 {a creative use of d5} Kh8 {the same
Ivanchuk shows to us how to solve Black's problems} ({his old game went} 16...
Nc6 17. Rad1 Rd7 18. Qc3 $1 Nb8 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Rd3 h6 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 22. h4
$16 {White enjoys a pleasant advantage, not only because of the pressure
against d6, but the Nb8 is out of play and he can create new weaknesses in
Black's camp by means of a4. Ivanchuk won with great technique in Ivanchuk, V 
(2750)-Topalov,V (2783) Morelia/ Linares 24th 2007 (2) 1-0}) 17. Nxe7 Qxe7 18.
Rad1 Rb6 {the best way to organize Black's defense} (18... Rd8 $2 19. Nxe5) 19.
Qe3 Rc6 (19... Nd7 $2 20. Nxe5 $1 dxe5 21. Rxd7 $16) 20. Rd2 Nd7 21. Qa7 Rfc8 {
and Black is ok} 22. Rfd1 (22. Nxe5 $2 R6c7 $19) 22... R8c7 23. Qa8+ Rc8 24.
Qa7 R8c7 $11 {Karjakin,S (2760)-Ivanchuk,V (2729) 11th Kings Rapid 2017 rapid
2017 (1.2) 1/2-1/2}) (10. Qe2 {is a different move order, White intends to
save time in development, but as he has not enough control over d5 right now,
Black can play actively} b5 $1 11. Bb3 h6 $1 (11... Nbd7 $2 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13.
Ng5 {[%csl Ge6]}) 12. Rfd1 (12. a3 $5 {just prevents b4} Nc6 13. Rfd1 Qc7 14.
Nd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 {Black achieved a nice position with the
remarkable idea} Nb8 $1 {[%cal Yb8d7,Yd7f6] and the knight is quickly replaced
to protect d5} 17. Re1 Nd7 18. Bc1 Rac8 19. c3 Rfd8 20. h3 Qc4 21. Qc2 Nf6 $11
{Jakovenko,D (2667)-Bu,X (2664) Taiyuan schev 2006 (9) 0-1}) (12. Nh4 $5 {
is an aggressive attempt of taking advantage of Black's slightly commited
kingside, but White is not well developed enough for such ideas:} b4 $1 13. Na4
Nbd7 {[%csl Ya4,Yh4] both knights look a bit misplaced, she tried to solve it
with} 14. Ng6 {but after} Bxb3 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. axb3 Nxe4 17. Qc4 Nef6 18.
Qxb4 Qe6 {Black had no problems - Muzychuk,M (2503)-Edouard,R (2658) Gibraltar
Masters 12th 2014 (6) 0-1}) 12... Nbd7 13. a3 $1 {securing the Nc3. Now, a
difficult move to remember is} (13. a4 $6 {is not only harmless, it was also
easier for Black after} b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Qc7 17. Ne1 Nf6
18. Rd3 Qc6 $1 {[%cal Yd6d5]} 19. Bd2 a5 20. f3 {Golizadeh,A (2504)-Ghaem
Maghami,E (2604) IRI-ch Tabriz 2011 (10) 0-1} Rfe8 $15 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 13...
Qe8 $5 {which was played a long time ago by the great Kasparov, but it shows
Kasparov's excellent preparation and profound understanding. Black has Nc5 now
