Gd3b4]} (14. Nh4 Nc5 $1 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Yg6] Protecting the
g6-square is the first reason why the queen stands well on e8.} 17. Nf3 {
[%csl Ge5]} b4 $1 18. Nb1 Qb5 $1 {with active play for Black, despite the pawn
weaknesses,} 19. Qxb5 axb5 20. Nbd2 bxa3 21. bxa3 c4 {[%csl Ya3]}) 14... Rc8 {
[%cal Yc8c3] White should prevent the typical exchange sacrifice first} 15. f3
Nc5 16. Ba2 (16. Bxe6 fxe6 {is ok for Black}) 16... Bxa2 17. Rxa2 Ne6 18. Nd3
a5 $1 {once more the queen is excellently placed on e8 and allows Black to
stop the knight's journey to d5.} 19. Nc1 $1 {[%csl Yb5] ; Short,N (2645)
-Kasparov, G (2795) Horgen 1995 (5) 1/2-1/2} Nc7 {[%cal Ye8c6,Yf8d8] would be
very solid now, continuing with Qc6 and Rfd8 and a nice position, for example}
20. Nb3 (20. Bb6 b4 $1 21. axb4 axb4 22. Bxc7 Rxc7 23. Nb5 Rd7 {[%cal Yd6d5]
It is funny because the Black pieces seem cramped, but he is about to free his
position with d6-d5} 24. c4 bxc3 25. Nxc3 d5 $1 26. exd5 Bc5+ 27. Kh1 Bd4 28.
Ra5 Qc8 29. N1a2 Rfd8 $11 {[%csl Yd5]}) (20. a4 b4 21. Nb5 d5 $1 {also
equalizes} 22. Nxc7 Rxc7 23. exd5 Rd7 $11) 20... b4 21. axb4 axb4 22. Na4 Ra8
$1 $11 {[%cal Ye8c6] the position is balanced, but I think the White pieces
are a bit misplaced now, and very far from their objective - the d5-square.})
10... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5] Probably the most solid way to equalize for Black.} (
10... Qc7 {[%cal Yf8c8] is another option}) ({and Vachier Lagrave tried} 10...
b5 $5 {recently. It is always nice to have more than one option in such
variations, in order to create unexpected problems to your opponent, so you
can check these two lines later - Puranik, A (2547) -Vachier Lagrave, M (2780)
chess.com IoM Masters 2018 (2.2) 0-1}) 11. Qe2 (11. Bg5 {is also often played,
and it is very important for Black to understand this position in order to not
fall into an unpleasant position: White aims for the exchange Bxf6 and then
mobilize his remaining pieces around d5, for example, Nd2-c4-e3 or Nd2-f1-e3.
The right move now is} Nd7 $1 {preserving the knights on the board which are
very important to keep control over d5, offering instead the dark-squared
bishop, which is Black's most useless piece in this structure.} ({I realized
this the hard way by playing} 11... Na5 {and allowing} 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. Nd5
Nxb3 14. cxb3 $5 {which gave White an easier game and a small but undisputed
advantage. Such positions do not depend on the "absolute truth", they are just
unpleasant to play as Black, even if no serious problem is apparent, the
position is a bit annoying as the bishops do not have open lines and d5 is
firmly under White's control, and often this is enough to leave Black with
difficult practical decisions, that may result in mistakes.} Bg5 15. Qd3 Rc8
16. Rfd1 g6 17. h3 f5 $6 {this way of looking for "counterplay" only succeeds
to create (more) weaknesses in Black's camp. True, it is hard to stay put...}
18. Nc3 Rc6 19. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Yf3e5]} Bf6 20. exf5 $1 {[%cal Gf3d4]} Bxf5 21.
Rd2 $14 {[%csl Yd5,Ye4] White has the better pawn structure, nice squares to
put his knights and the Black king tends to be more exposed, Black has a
difficult defense ahead and was not able to hold in Erenburg, S (2587)
-Quintiliano,R (2429) World Open - Washington (9.11) 1-0}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13.
Nd5 (13. Qe2 {improving the position before occupying d5, Black can keep
playing solidly} Nf6 14. Rad1 Bg4 $5 {[%cal Yc6d4]} 15. Qe3 Rac8 16. Rd2 Na5
17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. h3 Nxb3 19. axb3 Be6 $1 {[%csl Yd5] as we can see, the
important thing for Black in this line is to be sure that he is able to keep
the pieces necessary to protect d5 on the board. White tried} 20. b4 $5 h6 21.
b5 {looking to create new weaknesses or increase the pressure, but after} axb5
22. Nxb5 d5 $1 {Black equalized} 23. exd5 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 Bxd5 25. Nxe5 Rxc2 26.
Nc3 Bc6 $11 {Caruana,F (2757)-Anand,V (2780) Zuerich Chess Challenge 2013 (1)
1/2-1/2}) 13... Qd8 14. Qe2 (14. c3 Na5 15. Bc2 Nc4 16. b3 Na3 $1 {the knight
seems misplaced on a3, but actually it does a great job there.} 17. Ne3 (17.
Bd3 Bxd5 $1 18. exd5 f5 19. Be2 Qf6 20. c4 b5 $1 21. Qc1 b4 {[%cal Yd7c5,Ya6a5,
Ya5a4] with a great position for Black}) 17... Nxc2 18. Qxc2 Rc8 19. Rfd1 Rc6
20. Rac1 b5 $11 {Carlsen,M (2690)-Anand,V (2779) Corus Wijk aan Zee 2007 (4) 1/
2-1/2 one example that Black is very solid is the possible line} 21. Qd2 Qe7
22. c4 bxc4 23. Nxc4 Bxc4 24. Rxc4 Rxc4 25. bxc4 {[%csl Rd6]} Rb8 $1 {and the
back rank problems allow Black to defend both pawns.} 26. h3 Rb6 $11 {[%csl
Ya6,Yd6][%cal Gd7c5]}) (14. Qd2 {Leko,P (2723) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2758)
Beijing Sportaccord blitz 2014 (10) 1-0} Nc5 15. Qe3 Rc8 16. Rad1 Nxb3 17. axb3
Bxd5 $1 18. exd5 (18. Rxd5 $2 Nb4) 18... Ne7 {[%cal Yc8c2,Gf7f5,Gh7h6] and
Black is more than fine}) 14... Nc5 15. Rad1 Kh8 $5 {[%cal Yf7f5] preparing to
look for counterplay on the kingside, but f5 is usually the only way to
contest White's control in the center.} 16. h3 f5 17. Nc3 Nxb3 18. axb3 fxe4
19. Nxe4 d5 {this position seems very tense and was played only once, but the
analysis shows that Black is not worse in the arising complications.} 20. Nc3 {
Ambarcumova,K (2227) -Romanko,M (2226) Moscow op (Women) 2009 (5) 1-0} (20. Nc5
Bf5 $1 21. Nxe5 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5]} 22. Rxd5 Rae8 23. Re1 Nb4 $1 {and
White should sacrifice the exchange} 24. Qd2 $1 Nxd5 25. Qxd5 Rd8 26. Qc4 {
[%cal Ge5g6]} Qf6 27. Qe2 Rd5 28. b4 $44 {the position remains complex, but
Black has at least the draw with} Bxh3 $5 29. gxh3 Rxe5 $1 30. Qxe5 Qxf2+ $11)
(20. Rfe1 $5 Re8 $1 21. Nc5 Bg8 $1 $13 {[%csl Yd5,Ye5] the b7-pawn is
untouchable, but the central pawns are well protected now and can give good
dynamic chances for Black}) 20... Re8 $1 21. Rd2 (21. Nxe5 Nxe5 22. Qxe5 Bg4
$15) 21... d4 22. Ne4 Bd5 $13 {both sides have chances here, but since the
whole idea of this system is to obtain a slightly easier position with play
free of risk for White, Black managed to provoke favorable changes in the
position's nature.}) 11... Na5 {[%csl Gb3] The light-squared bishop exerts
some pressure on Black's position, so this exchange is welcome.} 12. Rfd1 Nxb3
13. axb3 (13. cxb3 $5 {is a tricky idea, as White opens the c-file to make it
harder for Black to find a decent square to put the queen. But this problem
can be solved with a nice idea:} Qe8 $1 {the queen is well placed on e8 for
many reasons.} 14. Ne1 {[%cal Ye1c2,Yc2b4,Yb4d5] the other idea behind 13.cxb3
was to vacate c2 to allow the knight's journey to d5.} (14. Bg5 Nh5 $1 {
again precise, preventing White from achieving favorable exchanges, and if}
15. Nxe5 $2 {[%csl Gh5]} f6 $1 $19 {[%cal Re8h5] and Black wins a piece thanks
to the Qe8 :)}) 14... Ng4 $1 15. Nc2 f5 $1 {[%cal Ye8g6] and another point of
Qe8 is revealed: The queen is ready to take an active position on the kingside.
} 16. exf5 (16. f3 {has lead to many exchanges} Nxe3 17. Nxe3 fxe4 18. Nxe4 Rd8
19. Nd5 {even though White's position seems great, he lacks some stability.}
Qf7 20. Qd3 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Qxd5 22. Rxd5 Kf7 $1 {[%cal Gf7e6] This endgame
seems better for White but, in reality, he is never able to improve the pieces
or change his set-up in a favorable way - Carlsen, M (2698)-Karjakin, S (2672)
Cap d'Agde KO rapid 2006 (2.2) 0-1}) 16... Bxf5 17. Nb4 Qg6 18. Nbd5 Rae8 {
Black managed to develop all of the pieces in an active way and also decreased
the opponent's control in the center resulting in a decent position.} 19. f3
Nxe3 20. Nxe7+ Rxe7 21. Qxe3 Ref7 {this is a nice example of which pieces
should be kept: If Black was left with the dark-squared bishop, he would face
